2.1.1 Introduction and Terminology
----------------------------------

A script is a text file that contains the source code of an interpreted
programming language.  An APL script is a text file that contains APL
commands (like )LOAD or )OFF) and APL expressions like 1 2 3+ 4 5 6.  In
GNU APL a script can also contains instructions for the well-known
вҲҮ-editor in order to create defines functions.

   On most platforms are the lines of a script separated by the single
ASCII character linefeed (LF, ASCII code 10); on Microsoft operating
systems the lines are separated by two characters carriage return (CR,
ASCII code 13) and (LF. ASCII code 10).  GNU APL ignores CR in most
contexts so that the same APL script can be executed on both kinds of
platforms.

   The first line of a script is called the shebang line.  The shebang
line determines how and with which arguments the script shall be
executed.  When the operating system (or, more precisely: a shell of the
operating system) executes a script then it parses the shebang line and
calls a function execve whose arguments are the result of that parsing.
Much of how GNU APL handles APL scripts can be learned by consulting the
man page for function execve.  To quote that man page:

         ...

     Interpreter scripts
            An  interpreter script is a text file that has execute permission enabled and whose
            first line is of the form:

                #!interpreter [optional-arg]

            The interpreter must be a valid pathname for an executable file.

            If the pathname argument of execve() specifies an interpreter script,
            then interpreter will be invoked with the following arguments:

                interpreter [optional-arg] pathname arg...

            where pathname is the absolute pathname of the file specified as the
            first argument of execve(), and arg... is the series of words pointed
            to by the argv argument of execve(), starting at argv[1]. Note that
            there is no way to get the argv[0] that was passed to the execve()
            call.

         ...

   It is important to note the singular in [optional-arg] above.
Traditionally the interpreter would have been /usr/local/bin/apl (if GNU
APL was installed in directory /usr/local/bin/ or else /usr/bin/apl (if
GNU APL was installed in directory /usr/bin/).  These days, however, it
has become common practice not to call the interpreter directly, but to
call the program /usr/bin/env as the interpreter and passing the real
interpreter (i.e.  /usr/local/bin/apl or apl) to /bin/env.  For example:

     Traditional shebang line (full path to the interpreter):

         #!/usr/local/bin/apl --script

     Traditional shebang line (interpreter name only):

         #!apl --script

     Contemporary shebang line:

         #!/bin/env -S apl --script

   For a single argument the shebang lines above have essentially the
same effect.  The long form (full path to the interpreter) is needed
only if the interpreter interpreter can not be found in one of the
directories listed in the environment variable $PATH, for example if a
user installs GNU APL in a non-standard directory (i.e.  other than in
/bin, /usr/bin, or /usr/local/bin).

   A minor disadvantage of using env as the interpreter is that execve()
is called twice: first by the shell to run env and then by env to run
apl.

   A potential advantage of using /bin/env as the interpreter is the -S
option of /bin/env which works around the single argument limitation of
execve.  However, this advantage only to programs other than GNU APL
because GNU APL comes with a built-in capability that is essentially
doing the same as the -S option of /bin/env.  Another, more important,
aspect is portability.  On a GNU/Linux system the standard shells (bash,
dash) seem to pass multiple arguments in the shebang line to the
interpreter in a way that GNU APL understands.  Whether all systems
behave in the same way is, however, not known.  Therefore using /bin/env
(with multiple arguments quoted) might be a more portable approach than
starting GNU APL directly.

   For multiple arguments the situation is more tricky and the two
methods differ slightly.  The /bin/env method requires that multiple
arguments are being quoted in the shebang line (so that they beconme a
single argument which env -S splits into several arguments passed to
execve).  the direct apl method does the same, but without the need to
quote multiple arguments in the shebang line.  For example:

         #!apl --script --id 1010

         #!/bin/env -S apl "--script --id 1010"

   A nasty pitfall of /bin/env is not to quote multiple arguments:

     $ cat SCRIPT2.apl
     #!/usr/bin/env -S apl --id 1010

     $ ./SCRIPT2.apl
     unknown option './SCRIPT2.apl'
     ...

     $ cat SCRIPT3.apl
     #!/usr/bin/env apl --id 1010

     $ b./SCRIPT2.apl
     /usr/bin/env: вҖҳapl --id 1010вҖҷ: No such file or directory
     /usr/bin/env: use -[v]S to pass options in shebang lines


