2.1.4 Starting GNU APL Scripts: a Conclusion
--------------------------------------------

The different methods for starting a GNU APL described above have
emerged over time.  They can be seen as different front-ends to the GNU
APL interpreter that slightly differ in how command line options are
being passed from the shell to GNU APL. However, sooner or later each of
the methods wiil call execve(pathname, argv, envp) where:

   вҖў pathname is the name or absolute path to the GNU APL interpreter,
   вҖў argv is the command line arguments for the GNU APL interpreter, and
   вҖў envp is the environment variables for the GNU APL interpreter.

   The different front-ends differ slightly as to how argv and envp are
being constructed; /bin/env allows the user to modify the environment
before the GNU APL interpreter is called, input redirection allows the
user to modifu the apl script file before the GNU APL interpreter is
called, and -f allows the user to select the script file to be executed.
One method may be simpler to use in one situation and another method may
be simpler to use in another situation and the final verdict as to which
method is the best is left to the user.


File: apl.info,  Node: How command line arguments are handled,  Next: Helpful Features for Scripting,  Prev: Starting GNU APL Scripts: a Conclusion,  Up: APL Scripting

2.1.5 How command line arguments are handled
--------------------------------------------

As we have seen, GNU APL can be started directly (by entering the name
of the GNU APL binary in the command line of a shell, or indirectly by
entering the name of a script that provides the name of the GNU APL
binary in the first line of the script.  In the latter case, the shell
uses function execve() to start APL, and one can provide additional
arguments that are passed on to APL. We briefly discuss both cases:

   0.  General Remark

   There is a convention in (not only) GNU APL, that the command line
options (and possibly an optional option argument) that occur left of
вҖҳ--вҖҷ are options directed to (and understood by) the APL interpreter
while the options right of вҖҳ--вҖҷ are passed to the APL application (and
their exact format is then defined by the APL application).  All command
line options that were used to start APL can later be retrieved with the
system variable вҺ•ARG in APL.

   Example 1: APL started directly

   We start APL with some command line options and display them with
вҺ•ARG. The command line options for the interpreter are вҖ“silent, -l, and
37, while the options app1 and app2 are for the APL application:

     $ apl --silent -l 37 -- app1 app2
           вҠғвҺ•ARG
     apl
     --silent
     -l
     37
     --
     app1
     app2

   Example 2: APL started indirectly

   A script is a text file which has execute permissions.  The first
line of a script, commonly known as the shebang of the script, has a
special format which specifies how the subsequent lines of the script
file shall be processed, see man execve for details.

   A GNU APL script is then a script whose shebang indicates the apl
binary as the interpreter for the subsequent lines where those
subsequent lines are either APL commands or APL statements.  With some
limitations, executing such an APL script yields the same result as
entering the subsequent lines in immediate execution mode.

   When APL is started directly, there is only one (possibly empty) set
of command line options, which are processed by the shell and then
passed to the apl binary.

   Starting APL indirectly refers to executing an APL script.  In this
case there are two sets of command line options:

   вҖў those passed to the script as command line arguments, and
   вҖў those in the shebang line of the script

   When the APL script is started, possibly with command line arguments,
the command line arguments entered by the user are combined with the
arguments in the shebang line of the script in a way that is described
in вҖҷman 2 execveвҖҷ.

   Assume the script file SCRIPT.apl contains this (the file is shipped
with GNU APL):

     # !/usr/bin/env -S apl "--script --id 1010"

           вҠғвҺ•ARG     вҚқ show command line options
           )OFF      вҚқ leave the interpreter

   Assume further that the script is started like this:

     $ ./SCRIPT.apl -- sarg1 sarg2

   Then the following output, which shows the order of command line
options as seen by вҺ•ARG, is produced:

     --script
     --id
     1010
     ./SCRIPT.apl
     --
     sarg1
     sarg2

   In the example above please note the following:

   вҖў вҖ“ separates the arguments passed to the interpreter (left of вҖ“)
     from the arguments passed to the APL application,
   вҖў The first line of the text file SCRIPT.apl is commonly referred to
     as the shebang line.  If the shebang contains more than one
     argument (like вҖ“script, вҖ“id, and 1010 above), then the arguments
     need to be quoted, and then the arguments must be quoted, and
   вҖў in contrast, multiple arguments in the command line (like sarg1 and
     sarg2 above) must not be quoted (or else they will appear as a
     single argument).

   вҺ•ARG shows the arguments in the shebang line and in the command line
in the following order:

  1. Interpreter name (the first name in the shebang, here: apl)
  2. Optional Interpreter argument(s) (here: вҖ“script, вҖ“id, and 1010)
  3. Script filename (here: ./SCRIPT.apl)
  4. Optional Script argument(s) (here: вҖ“, sarg1, and sarg2)

   CAUTION: as discussed in вҖҷman 2 execveвҖҷ the interpretation of the
optional interpreter arguments (2.  above) is system specific and
possibly not portable.  For that reason the optional interpreter
argument should not be omitted (you can use вҖ“ to provide at least one
argument) and also not more than one argument.  On GNU/Linux systems the
following shebang lines of the script are understood:

     #!/usr/bin/env -S apl "--script --id 1010"
     #! /usr/local/bin/apl
     #! /usr/local/bin/apl --
     #! /usr/local/bin/apl -s
     #! /usr/local/bin/apl --script
     #! /usr/local/bin/apl -s --
     #! /usr/local/bin/apl --script --

   The recommended form is: вҖҳ|/usr/local/bin/apl --script|вҖҷ.

   Note that вҖҳ-вҖҷ and any options that follow it in the shebang line MAY
OR MAY NOT be included in вҺ•ARG (this depends on the platform used).  In
contrast, options that follow вҖҳ-вҖҷ in the script command line WILL BE
shown since this is controlled by GNU APL and not by the platform.
There is normally no point in passing any application options in the
shebang line to APL because such parameters can more easily be provided
directly further down in the script.  However, in cases where the script
has only application options it may be convenient to make -- the last
option of the shebang so that the user of the script need not specify it
manually.

   Using вҖҳ0-вҖҷ in the shebang line of the script file usually prevents
subsequent options in the shebang line from being interpreted as APL
command line options (and, more importantly, from causing unknown option
errors when GNU APL starts).  At least under GNU/Linux with bash the
subsequent options will be passed to the APL application via вҺ•ARG.

   Depending on this exact behavior cannot be recommended.  A cleaner
approach is to use options starting with - or вҖҳ-вҖҷ only for the
interpreter options, and options starting with + for application
options.  This should work on all platforms because for strings, say,
APLOPT, ARG1, ARG2, ..., which contain no whitespace:

   вҖў +APLOPT is ignored, although shown in вҺ•ARG,
   вҖў ++APLOPT ARG1 is ignored, although shown in вҺ•ARG,
   вҖў +++APLOPT ARG1 ARG2 is ignored, although shown in вҺ•ARG,
   вҖў ...


