2.1.7 Double-quoted Strings
---------------------------

Standard APL literals (aka.  strings) such as вҖҷHelloвҖҷ are single quoted.
As a matter of convenience, GNU APL also provides double-quoted strings
which differ from single quoted strings in two ways:

   вҖў A standard single quoted APL string is a vector if its length вү  1
     but a scalar if its length = 1.  This is sometimes inconvenient and
     therefore double-quoted strings are more consistent in always being
     vectors regardless of their length.  In other words, вҖҷAвҖҷ is a
     scalar while "A" is a vector.

   вҖў Double-quoted strings understand the standard C escape sequences
     for control characters, such as \n for ASCII line feed, \t for
     ASCII TAB, etc.


File: apl.info,  Node: Multi-Line Strings,  Next: Multi-Line Literals,  Prev: Double-quoted Strings,  Up: APL Scripting

2.1.8 Multi-Line Strings
------------------------

A substantial disadvantage of вҺ•INP is that it only works in immediate
execution mode (and consequently also in .apl scripts), but not the
bodies of defined functions.  Multi-line strings fill this gap for
string literals that span several lines of text inside the body of
defined functions (as well as in immediate execution mode and in
scripts).  Multi-Line strings have become more and more advanced (and
elegant) over time.  For this reason they currently come in different
flavors (of which the older ones will eventually disappear).

* Menu:

