2.1.10 Automatic )MORE
----------------------

The GNU APL command )MORE provides, in some cases, additional
information about a prior APL error.  The availability of such
additional information is indicated by a + at the end of the error
message.  The additional information is automatically discarded when the
next non-empty line is entered.  For example:

           "ABC"[4]
     INDEX ERROR+
           'ABC'[4]
           ^    ^
           )MORE
     min index=вҺ•IO (=1), offending index=4, max index=вҺ•IO+2 (=3)
           в—Ҡ вҚқ clears )MORE

           )MORE
     NO )MORE ERROR INFO

   This is rather useful in purely interactive mode where the user can
issue the )MORE command directly after an APL error has occurred to help
figure out what exactly went wrong.  In a script, however, the standard
)MORE command (as inherited from IBM APL2) is fairly useless for two
reasons:

   вҖў A human user has a chance to issue the )MORE command interactively
     after an error has occurred, while a script continues after
     displaying the error message, and
   вҖў It is rather difficult to predict where the next errors will occur,
     i.e.  where to place the )MORE command in the script.

   To make the )MORE command more useful for scripts, in GNU APL it can
be augmented with an optional argument AUTO like this:

           )MORE AUTO ON
     Automatic )MORE is now: ON

           "ABC"[4]
     min index=вҺ•IO (=1), offending index=4, max index=вҺ•IO+2 (=3)
     INDEX ERROR+
           'ABC'[4]
           ^    ^

   If ON/OFF is omitted then the automatic )MORE mode is toggled.  The
additional )MORE information is displayed before the standard 3-line APL
error message.


File: apl.info,  Node: Script Example,  Prev: Automatic )MORE,  Up: APL Scripting

2.1.11 Script Example
---------------------

Note that the two different ways of running an APL script have an impact
on how вҺ•ARG looks like.  If stdin is redirected then there is only one
(possibly empty) set of command line options.  Otherwise there are two
sets of command line options: command line options for the apl
interpreter and command line options for the script.

   Consider the following simple script called SCRIPT.apl in directory
workspaces:

     #! /usr/local/bin/apl --script

     вҠғвҺ•ARG   вҚқ show command line options
     )OFF    вҚқ leave the interpreter

   If SCRIPT.apl is redirected to stdin of the APL interpreter:

      /usr/local/bin/apl --silent <  ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl

      or

      /usr/local/bin/apl --silent -f ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl

   then the first line вҖҳ#! /usr/local/bin/apl --scriptвҖҷ of file
SCRIPT.apl is merely a comment (GNU APL accepts both the traditional APL
character вҚқ and the character # as start of a comment).  The вҖҳ-scriptвҖҷ
option is therefore ignored and the following mix of input and output is
shown on the screen.  The input from the script is indented by the usual
APL prompt of 6 blanks, while the output of the APL interpreter is not
indented.

           #! /usr/local/bin/apl --script

           вҠғвҺ•ARG     вҚқ show command line options
           )OFF      вҚқ leave the interpreter

   If we run the same script directly:

     ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl

   Then we get:

      /usr/local/bin/apl --script ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl

   The вҖҳ-scriptвҖҷ implies вҖҳ-noCINвҖҷ so that the input lines for the
interpreter are no longer echoed to the output.  This is most likely
what you want when writing a script.

   Also, the first line of the script is no longer ignored as a comment,
but controls the command line argument (and thus вҺ•ARG) of the
interpreter.  The additional command line argument
вҖҳ../workspaces/SCRIPT.aplвҖҷ comes from function execve (see вҖҷman 2
execveвҖҷ).

   If we provide an argument, say SCRIPTARG, to SCRIPT.apl:

     ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl SCRIPTARG

   then it shows up at the end of вҺ•ARG:

      /usr/local/bin/apl --script ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl SCRIPTARG

   A final note on scripting in GNU APL is that the вҲҮ-editor works
slightly differently when it is used in a script.  If a user edits an
APL function interactively then an attempt to open an existing function
with a full header gives a DEFN ERROR:

           вҲҮZвҶҗFOO B
     [1] вҲҮ

           вҲҮZвҶҗFOO B
     DEFN ERROR+
           вҲҮZвҶҗFOO B
                  ^
           )MORE
     attempt to вҲҮ-open existing function with new function header

   In contrast to a user who can react to the DEFN ERROR, a script
cannot detect this situation and would continue to push lines (which
were intended to be the body of the defined function) into the APL
interpreter.  That would most likely cause fairly undesirable behavior.
For example, if the lines of a defined function start with line numbers
(like [1], [2], ...)  then every such line would give a SYNTAX ERROR,
and other errors can be expected as well.

   For that reason, if the вҲҮ-editor is used in a script and attempts to
redefine an existing defined function then the existing function is
simply overwritten with the new one and no DEFN ERROR is raised.


File: apl.info,  Node: Axis argument in defined functions,  Next: Function Groups,  Prev: APL Scripting,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.2 Axis argument in defined functions
======================================

Defined functions and operators (including lambdas) accept an axis
argument.  For example:

     вҲҮZвҶҗAverage[X] B
      ZвҶҗ(+/[X]B) Г· (вҚҙB)[X]
     вҲҮ

           Average[1] 5 5вҚҙвҚі25
     11 12 13 14 15

           Average[2] 5 5вҚҙвҚі25
     3 8 13 18 23

   Syntactically, the axis is used in the same way as for primitive
functions and operators.

   There are no constraints on the axis such as being integers.
Therefore you can use an axis as a third function argument.  Keep in
mind, however, that doing so will make your APL code incompatible with
other APL interpreters.  Use this feature carefully!


File: apl.info,  Node: Function Groups,  Next: Colored Output,  Prev: Axis argument in defined functions,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.3 Function Groups
===================

In the old APL1 every function of the interpreter was represented by a
single APL character.  More precisely, the character represented 1, 2,
or 3 sub-functions and the sub-function was selected by the number of
arguments provided:

   вҖў 1 for monadic functions,
   вҖў 2 or monadic functions with axis,
   вҖў 2 for dyadic functions (w/o axis), or
   вҖў 3 for dyadic functions with axis.

   The APL character itself was designed in a way that made it easy to
remember which functions it represented.

   Unfortunately this 1:1 relationship between APL characters and
interpreter functions did not scale very well.  As the number of
functions increased, a new and, at that time, better scalable concept
was introduced: вҺ•-functions (and variables).  The APL standards define
only a small number (less than 20) of them, but different APL vendors
were eagerly adding more system functions to represent their proprietary
extensions to th APL language.  And so did GNU APL. With вҺ•-functions the
original visual appearance that helped to remember the many functions
was replaced by abbreviations.  That is, for example, вҺ•AV stands for the
Atomic Vector, вҺ•TS for Time Stamp, and so forth.

   As of this writing, the GNU APL interpreter has more than 100
non-standard functions for various purposes.  For such a large number
the вҺ•-function approach is no longer scalable (try to remember 100
abbreviations and think about the readability of the code using them!).
Rather than adding a new вҺ•-function for every new function, GNU APL
tries to keep the number of вҺ•-functions as small as reasonable and by
grouping several interpreter functions into sub-function of a single
top-level вҺ•-function.

   We call such a top-level вҺ•-function a function group.  The
sub-function functions of a function group are somehow related by their
purpose.  The function groups of GNU APL are:

   вҖў вҢ№: a collection of matrix factorizations (aka.  decompositions)
   вҖў вҺ•CR: a collection of data conversions (formerly known as monadic
     Charater Representations
   вҖў вҺ•FFT: a collection of Fast Fourier Transformations
   вҖў вҺ•FIO: a collection of File I/O functions
   вҖў вҺ•MX: a collection of Matrix functions functions
   вҖў вҺ•RVAL: generation of Random APL Values
   вҖў SQL: an interface to SQL databases

   The syntax for function groups has evolved in 3 phases as elucidated
in the following.

* Menu:

* Phase 1: Numerical Axis Argument::
* Phase 2: String Axis Argument::
* Phase 3: Member Notation::
* Subfunction Lists::


File: apl.info,  Node: Phase 1: Numerical Axis Argument,  Next: Phase 2: String Axis Argument,  Up: Function Groups

2.3.1 Phase 1: Numerical Axis Argument
--------------------------------------

In the first phase, the number of functions per function group (at that
time вҺ•CR and вҺ•FIO) was fairly small.  A sub-function of the function
group was selected as follows:

   вҖў If all functions in the function group were monadic (as is the case
     in вҺ•CR), then the sub-function was selected by the left argument of
     the function group.
   вҖў Otherwise (as is the case in вҺ•FIO) the individual sub-function
     could be monadic, dyadic, or nomadic and the sub-function was
     selected by an axis argument of the function group.

   For example:

           4 вҺ•CR B          вҚқ format B in a "boxed" fashion
           18 вҺ•CR B         вҚқ convert APL string B to an UTF8-encoded byte vector

           вҺ•FIO[3] B        вҚқ fopen file B for reading
           A вҺ•FIO[3] B      вҚқ fopen file B with mode A

   In both cases was the sub-function selector an integer scalar.


File: apl.info,  Node: Phase 2: String Axis Argument,  Next: Phase 3: Member Notation,  Prev: Phase 1: Numerical Axis Argument,  Up: Function Groups

2.3.2 Phase 2: String Axis Argument
-----------------------------------

Shortly after introducing the syntax of phase 1, GNU APL users began to
develop an APL workspace named FILE_IO. This workspace contains one APL
wrapper function for each numerical вҺ•FIO sub-function selector.  These
wrappers were trivial one-liners like these:

           вҲҮZh вҶҗ As FIOвҲҶfopen Bs
           вҚқвҚқ fopen(Bs, As) filename Bs
            Zh вҶҗ As вҺ•FIO[3] Bs
           вҲҮ

           вҲҮZh вҶҗ FIOвҲҶfopen_ro Bs
           вҚқвҚқ fopen(Bs, "r") filename Bs
            Zh вҶҗ вҺ•FIO[3] Bs
           вҲҮ

   APL programs would )COPY this workspace and then use its normal
defined functions instead of вҺ•FIO with an axis argument or вҺ•CR with a
left argument.  The development of the FILE_IO suggested that APL users
have a preference of names over numbers to select a sub-function.

   GNU APL accommodated this preference by allowing sub-function names
(APL strings) as sub-function selectors.  These names were usually the
same as the C library function that implemented them.

   The phase 1 example above would now become the slightly better
readable:

           'style_boxed' вҺ•CR B        вҚқ format B in a "boxed" fashion
           'string_to_UTF8' вҺ•CR B     вҚқ convert APL string B to UTF8

           вҺ•FIO['fopen'] B            вҚқ fopen file B for reading
           A вҺ•FIO['fopen'] B          вҚқ fopen file B with mode A


File: apl.info,  Node: Phase 3: Member Notation,  Next: Subfunction Lists,  Prev: Phase 2: String Axis Argument,  Up: Function Groups

2.3.3 Phase 3: Member Notation
------------------------------

The third phase aims at further improving the readability.  It replaces
the axis argument with a member notation.  The phase 1 and 2 examples
above would now become:

           вҺ•CR.style_boxed B       вҚқ format B in a "boxed" fashion
           вҺ•CR.string_to_UTF8 B    вҚқ convert APL string B to UTF8

           вҺ•FIO.fopen B            вҚқ fopen file B for reading
           A вҺ•FIO.fopen B          вҚқ fopen file B with mode A


File: apl.info,  Node: Subfunction Lists,  Prev: Phase 3: Member Notation,  Up: Function Groups

2.3.4 Subfunction Lists
-----------------------

If the number of sub-functions becomes large, then remembering all
sub-function names of a function group is still a problem.  To avoid the
need to consult other documentation while programming, all function
groups provide lists that show their sub-functions and their syntax.

   Let FOO be a function group.  Then:

   вҖў FOO "" shows a list of sub-functions, and
   вҖў FOO вҚ¬ shows the syntaces (as per phase 1, 2, or 3) of them.


File: apl.info,  Node: Colored Output,  Next: Comparison Rules,  Prev: Function Groups,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.4 Colored Output
==================

The APL interpreter gets its input from the standard input (stdin),
which is normally connected to the userвҖҷs keyboard, but can also be a
file if APL scripting, the вҖҳfвҖҷ option, or the вҖҳTвҖҷ option is used.

   The APL interpreter prints its results on either the standard output
(stdout) for normal APL output, or to the error output (stderr) for
additional trouble-shooting information.

   You can print the 3 channels stdin, stdout, and stderr in different
colors by means of the debug command ]XTERM. Command ]XTERM ON enables
colored output while ]XTERM OFF disables it (for example to avoid
annoying ANSI Escape sequences when forwarding stdout or stderr to a
file).

   Default colored output assumes a terminal (-emulation) that
understands ANSI (or VT100) Escape sequences.  The xterm that comes with
most recent GNU/Linux distributions is a perfect choice supporting both
colors and UTF-8 (Unicode) encoded character I/O.

   Non-ANSI terminals, as well as other colors than the default ones,
can be configured in the вҖҷpreferencesвҖҷ file.  The вҖҷpreferencesвҖҷ file
also contains a description of all possible color settings.


File: apl.info,  Node: Comparison Rules,  Next: Complex Numbers,  Prev: Colored Output,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.5 Comparison Rules
====================

Both IBM APL2 and the ISO standard require that the arguments of <, вүӨ,
вүҘ, and > (but not of = or вү ) are integer or real numbers.  As a
consequence, the argument(s) of вҚӢ or вҚ’ (which require comparison) must
also be a vector of integer or real numbers.

   In contrast, GNU APL also allows the comparison of characters and
numbers or the comparison of complex numbers according to the following,
more general, rules.

   Let A and B be two APL values to be compared.  The final result of
comparing A and B is the first verdict (i.e.  either A < B, or A > B, or
A = B) obtained when following the rules below in the indicated order:

  1. Comparison by rank: if (вҚҙвҚҙA) < (вҚҙвҚҙB) then A < B and vice versa.

  2. Comparison by shape: if (вҚҙA) < (вҚҙB) then A < B and vice versa.  The
     first differing shape item (from the left) decides.

  3. Comparison of ravel elements: at this point (вҚҙA) вүЎ (вҚҙB). If all
     corresponding ravel elements of A and B are equal (i.e.  tolerantly
     equal within вҺ•CT as defined in the ISO standard) then A = B.

     Otherwise let A1 and B1 be the first corresponding ravel elements
     of A and B with A1 вү  B1.  If A1 < B1 then A < B and vice versa.
     The comparison A1 < B1 is made according to the following rules 4 -
     8 below.

  4. Comparison by depth:

        вҖў If A1 and B1 are both nested: the rules 1 - 3 above are
          (recursively) applied to corresponding ravel elements of вҠғA1
          and вҠғB1 until a verdict is obtained.

        вҖў if A1 is simple and B1 is nested then A < B and vice versa.

        вҖў otherwise (i.e.  A1 and B1 are both simple): A < B if A1 < B1
          according to rules 5 - 8 below and vice versa.

  5. Comparison by Unicode: if A1 and B1 are both character values and
     (вҺ•UCS A1) < (вҺ•UCS B1) then A < B and vice versa.

  6. Comparison by type: If A1 is a character and B1 is numeric, then A
     < B and vice versa.

  7. Comparison by numeric value: if A1 and B1 are both numeric values
     then:

        вҖў Comparison by real part: if (9в—ӢA1) < (9в—ӢB1) then A < B and
          vice versa.

        вҖў Comparison by imaginary part: otherwise if (11в—ӢA1) < (11в—ӢB1)
          then A < B and vice versa.

  8. Otherwise: A = B.

   Another way of describing the rules above is that the comparison of
two values is comprised of sub-comparisons of certain properties of the
values in the following order:

   вҖў the ranks of the values,
   вҖў the shapes of the values,
   вҖў the first differing ravel element (in row-major order) of the
     values,
   вҖў the depths of the differing ravel elements,
   вҖў the types (character vs.  numeric) of the differing ravel elements,
   вҖў the Unicodes of the differing ravel elements (if applicable)
   вҖў the real parts of numeric values,
   вҖў the imaginary parts of numeric values,

   Note: Rules 1 and 2 above are only relevant for comparisons made in
the context of sorting (i.e.  for вҚӢ or вҚ’).  This is because for =, вү , <,
вүӨ, вүҘ, or > either a RANK ERROR or a LENGTH ERROR is raised if the ranks
or shapes of A and B do not match:

           (9 8) < (1 2 3)
     LENGTH ERROR
           9 8<1 2 3
           ^  ^

           вҚӢ(9 8) (1 2 3)
     1 2

   The reason for comparing complex numbers first by their real parts
and then by their imaginary part and not, for example, first by their
magnitude and then by their angle is that the chosen order gives more
consistent results when comparing near-complex numbers or their true
real companions.  For example, a magnitude first comparison of complex
numbers would make ВҜ2 < ВҜ1 < ВҜ2J1EВҜ20 for the near-complex number
ВҜ2J1EВҜ20.

   CAUTION: The comparison of two strings (i.e.  nested character
vectors) may give unexpected results because shorter strings come before
longer strings.  For example, вҖҷZooвҖҷ comes before вҖҷAdamвҖҷ even though one
might expect the opposite.

           Z[вҚӢZ вҶҗ 'Adam' 'Zoo']
      Zoo Adam

           Z[вҚӢZ вҶҗ 'Adam' 'Zora']
      Adam Zora

   This pitfall can be avoided by enforcing the same length for all
strings being compared or sorted.  A simple way to achieve that is the
use of вҠӮ[2]вҠғ like this (assuming вҺ•IOвҶҗ1):

           Z[вҚӢZ вҶҗ вҠӮ[2]вҠғ 'Adam' 'Zoo']
      Adam Zoo

           Z[вҚӢZ вҶҗ вҠӮ[2]вҠғ 'Adam' 'Zora']
      Adam Zora


File: apl.info,  Node: Complex Numbers,  Next: Debug Commands,  Prev: Comparison Rules,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.6 Complex Numbers
===================

Complex numbers are fully supported.


File: apl.info,  Node: Debug Commands,  Next: Direct Functions (Lambdas),  Prev: Complex Numbers,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.7 Debug Commands
==================

In addition to the classical APL commands like )LOAD or )SAVE, GNU APL
has a number of debug commands for debugging purposes.  Regular APL
commands start with ) and print their output on stdout.  Debug commands
start with ] and print their output on stderr.  Normally you cannot
easily distinguish between stdout and stderr, but another GNU APL
feature, colored output, uses different colors for stdout and stderr.

   Type )HELP or ]HELP in the interpreter for a list of all commands
available.


