2.8 Direct Functions (Lambdas)
==============================

GNU APL supports direct functions (aka.  lambdas), but only in a rather
limited form.

* Menu:

* Named Lambdas::
* Unnamed Lambdas::
* Limitations of GNU APL Lambdas::


File: apl.info,  Node: Named Lambdas,  Next: Unnamed Lambdas,  Up: Direct Functions (Lambdas)

2.8.1 Named Lambdas
-------------------

A statement of the form

           FUN вҶҗ { body_statement }

   creates a named lambda.  The single body_statement may contain the
special variable names вҚә and вҚө as well as the special function names вҚ¶
and вҚ№ which are replaced by the actual arguments of the lambda when the
lambda is executed.  The valence of the lambda is determined as follows:

   вҖў If вҚ¶ and вҚ№ are present then the lambda is a dyadic operator.
   вҖў If only вҚ¶ is present then the lambda is a monadic operator.
   вҖў If neither вҚ¶ nor вҚ№ is present then the lambda is a normal defined
     function.
   вҖў If both вҚә and вҚө are present in the body_statement then the operator
     or defined function is dyadic.
   вҖў If only вҚө is present then the operator or defined is monadic.
   вҖў If neither вҚә nor вҚө is present then the lambda is niladic.
   вҖў Lambdas with the left value argument вҚә but without the right value
     argument вҚө are invalid (SYNTAX ERROR).

   There is a noteworthy pitfall related to niladic named lambdas.
Recalling to the fundamental APL evaluation rule:

   All functions execute according to their position in an expression.
The rightmost function whose arguments are available is evaluated first

   implies that a niladic function is evaluated first (because it has no
arguments and consequently no arguments that are not available).
Therefore in an expression such as:

     NAME вҶҗ { statement }

   will the niladic lambda { statement } be evaluated before the
assignment, The name NAME is therefore the result of the niladic lambda
and not the niladic lambda itself.  IOW: the example above does not
create a niladic named lambda, but rather a normal variable NAME whose
value is the result of evaluating statement.  Creating niladic named
lambdas is impossible.

   GNU APL supports an axis argument in normal defined functions and
operators.  In lambda expressions the Greek letter ПҮ (Chi) is the
variable name for an axis argument.

   The way a named lambda is implemented in GNU APL is that the
assignment of the form:

           FUN вҶҗ { body_expression }

   is translated to a two-line function вҺ•FX вҖҷlambda_headerвҖҷ
вҖҷbody_expressionвҖҷ.

   For example:

           )FNS

           SUM вҶҗ { вҚә + вҚө }

   is translated to a two-line function вҺ•FX вҖҷlambda_headerвҖҷ
вҖҷbody_expressionвҖҷ.

   For example:

           )FNS

           SUM вҶҗ { вҚә + вҚө }
           )FNS
     SUM

           вҲҮSUM[вҺ•]вҲҮ
     DEFN ERROR+
           вҲҮSUM[вҺ•]вҲҮ
                  ^
           )MORE
     function is a lambda

   Named lambdas are included in function lists like )FNS along with
other defined functions.  They can not be edited with the вҲҮ-edidor, but
can be displayed using вҺ•CR вҖҷnameвҖҷ:

           вҺ•CR 'SUM'
     О»вҶҗвҚә О»1 вҚө
     О»вҶҗ вҚә + вҚө

   The lambda_header is automatically deduced from the presence or
absence of the variable names (вҚә, вҚө, and ПҮ) and function names (вҚ¶ and вҚ№)
in the body_expression and from whether the body_expression is empty (no
О»вҶҗ) or not (i.e.  with О»вҶҗ).

   It is possible to specify local variables that work exactly like
their companions in normal defined functions.  Please note that this is
different from some other APL interpreters which treat all variables in
lambda bodies as local variables.  The syntax for specifying local
variables is the same as for the header in normal defined functions:
they are added at the end with semicolons as separators.  In the above
example one could add local variables C and D like this:

           SUM вҶҗ { вҚә + вҚө ;C;D }

           вҺ•CR 'SUM'
     О»вҶҗвҚә О»1 вҚө;C;D
     О»вҶҗ вҚә + вҚө

   If a named lambda is created inside a defined function, then the name
of the lambda (i.e.  the name left of вҶҗ { ...  }) can be made a local
variable of the function in which the named lambda is created.  This
creates a lambda with local scope.

   Please note that the above only describes the current implementation
of named lambda in GNU APL. A consequence of that implementation is that
the symbols вҚә, вҚө, ПҮ, вҚ¶, вҚ№, and О» are pretty much behaving like user
defined variables.  In particular, they can be used outside named or
unnamed lambdas.  However, that may change in the future and therefore
such use of вҚә, вҚө, ПҮ, вҚ¶, вҚ№, and О» outside is certainly a bad idea.

   As of this writing, GNU APL lambdas allow multiple statements,
separated by в—Ҡ.  This feature is experimental, not portable, and should
be avoided where possible.  In GNU APL, the value of a multi-statement
lambda is the value of the last statement and this differs from the
semantics of multi-statements in other APL interpreters!


File: apl.info,  Node: Unnamed Lambdas,  Next: Limitations of GNU APL Lambdas,  Prev: Named Lambdas,  Up: Direct Functions (Lambdas)

2.8.2 Unnamed Lambdas
---------------------

An unnamed lambda is an expression inside { and } but without assigning
it to a name.  This is often used together with the EACH operator.  For
example:

           { вҚҙ , вҚө } ВЁ 'a' 'ab' 'abc'
      1  2  3

   Unnamed lambdas are automatically local in scope (similar to labels).
They can be passed as function arguments to operators.  However, unnamed
lambdas are NOT inserted into the symbol table of the interpreter.  They
are therefore not visible to functions like вҺ•CR or by the вҲҮ-editor.
Occasionally the names О»1, О»2, ...  may show up in commands like )SIS.
These names are automatically generated for unnamed lambdas in order to
provide a name in places where a function name is needed.


File: apl.info,  Node: Limitations of GNU APL Lambdas,  Prev: Unnamed Lambdas,  Up: Direct Functions (Lambdas)

2.8.3 Limitations of GNU APL Lambdas
------------------------------------

There are a number of features related to lambdas that are present in
other APL interpreters but that are NOT implemented in GNU APL. This
includes multiple statements, guards, lexical scoping, and probably
more.

   The primary reason for these limitations in not the lazyness of the
GNU APL author, but the fact that the lambdas in other APL dialects
introduce a execution semantics that is very different from the
execution semantics of properly defined functions (i.e.  those created
with the вҲҮ-editor or with вҺ•FX. For example, a properly defined function
returns with вҶ’0 or after its last line was executed, while the lambdas
in other dialects also returns after the first non-committed value was
computed (i.e.  in the middle of a multi-line function and without any
вҶ’0 (and without any warnings).  The GNU APL author is an old-fashioned
programmer from the APL1 aera who considers it outright dangerous to
have two kinds of functions that very much look the same (the only
difference being the argument names вҚә and вҚө), but that behave
fundamentally different.

   In contrast, GNU APL tries to keep the same execution semantics for
lambdas and for properly defined functions.  As one of the consequences,
you should not create or modify a lambdas with вҺ•FX or with the вҲҮ-editor
(it may be possible for debugging purposes, but then it is asking for
trouble).


