2.9 Commands )COPY_ONCE, )DUMP, and DUMP-HTML
=============================================

In standard APL, workspaces are processed with the standard commands
)LOAD, )COPY, and )SAVE. GNU APL provides additional commands to process
workspaces.

* Menu:

* )DUMP Command::
* )DUMP-HTML Command::
* )COPY_ONCE Command::


File: apl.info,  Node: )DUMP Command,  Next: )DUMP-HTML Command,  Up: Commands )COPY_ONCE )DUMP and DUMP-HTML

2.9.1 )DUMP Command
-------------------

GNU APL has a command )DUMP that saves a workspace to disk, similar to
the )OUT command.  The difference between them is the file format being
produced.  While )OUT produces a file in IBMвҖҷs workspace interchange
format (aka.  an .atf file), )DUMP produces a file in GNU APLвҖҷs script
format (i.e.  readable APL statements).  Files written with )DUMP can be
edited with normal text editors (vi, Emacs), read back with "apl -f", or
made executable (see scripting).


File: apl.info,  Node: )DUMP-HTML Command,  Next: )COPY_ONCE Command,  Prev: )DUMP Command,  Up: Commands )COPY_ONCE )DUMP and DUMP-HTML

2.9.2 )DUMP-HTML Command
------------------------

The )DUMP-HTML command is similar to the )DUMP command and the output
format is similar as well.  The difference is that those characters that
need HTML-escaping (e.g.  вҖҷ<вҖҷ becomes &lt; and вҖҷ>вҖҷ becomes вҖҷ&gt; etc.)
are HTML-escaped.  The output of the )DUMP-HTML command can therefore be
directly used by a web browser to display workspace listings (to share
the code).

   The files written with the )DUMP-HTML command have the extension
.html.

   In addition to the APL code, the .html files produced have a short
HTML <head> section template.  The user should replace the fields marked
with ??????  with proper values (for the author, the copyright owner,
and a short description) before publishing the page.


File: apl.info,  Node: )COPY_ONCE Command,  Prev: )DUMP-HTML Command,  Up: Commands )COPY_ONCE )DUMP and DUMP-HTML

2.9.3 )COPY_ONCE Command
------------------------

Command )COPY_ONCE copies all objects (variables, functions and
operators) from some other workspace into the current workspace similar
to )COPY. However, )COPY_ONCE does this only once; a second invocation
of )COPY_ONCE with the same workspace (and the same library reference
number) is silently ignored.  This speeds up the )COPYing of libraries
that occur in several )DUMP-ed or )SAVE-ed workspaces.


File: apl.info,  Node: ]DOXY Command,  Next: ]KEYB Command,  Prev: Commands )COPY_ONCE )DUMP and DUMP-HTML,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.10 ]DOXY Command
==================

A particularly useful debug command is ]DOXY. It dumps the current
workspace in brows-able HTML format with listings of defined functions
and hyperlinks between them.

     ]DOXY                   вҚқ write documentation to /tmp/WSNAME/*
     ]DOXY dest              вҚқ write documentation to dest/WSNAME/*

   The starting point for browsing the documentation are the files:

     /tmp/WSNAME/index.html         вҚқ for ]DOXY without arguments, or
     dest/WSNAME/index.html         вҚқ for e.g. ]DOXY dest

   The index.html files above usually correspond to the following URIs
in your browser:

     file:///tmp/WSNAME or
     file:///absolute-path-to-dest/WSNAME respectively.

   In the above examples WSNAME is the )WSID of the workspace in which
the ]DOXY command was executed.

   One can (and should make it a habit to) insert special comments into
defined functions which are copied into proper places inside the
documentation that is generated by the ]DOXY command.  These "doxy"
comments begin with вҚқвҚқ (as opposed to "normal" APL comments that start
with a single вҚқ.  Doxy comments are typically one-liners that briefly
explain what a function is supposed to do.

   For example:

     вҲҮZвҶҗA SUM B
      вҚқвҚқ Return the sum of A and B          вҶҗ ]DOXY comment:  (double вҚқ)
      вҚқ  A: numeric                         вҶҗ "normal" APL comments (single вҚқ) ...
      вҚқ  B: numeric
      ZвҶҗA + B
     вҲҮ

   But please note the following: in the original doxygen program (for
C, C++, or other languages) source code lines may be a mix of code and
comments (including doxygen comments).  In the ]DOXY command of GNU APL
a line of a defined function shall be either APL code or else a doxygen
comment (i.e.  starting with вҚқвҚқ).  Doxygen comments indented with blanks
are allowed (for the sake of readability).

   Since a doxygen comment is also a valid APL comment, it is perfectly
legal to put a doxygen comment at the end of a line that starts with APL
code.  However, such lines will be ignored by the ]DOXY command.

   The parser generates no extra code from the doxygen comments, and
therefore the use of many doxygen comments causes no performance problem
(and neither do regular APL comments).


File: apl.info,  Node: ]KEYB Command,  Next: ]NEXTFILE and ]PUSHFILE Commands,  Prev: ]DOXY Command,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.11 ]KEYB Command
==================

In the early days of APL the user was typically faced with three
problems: APL keyboards, APL screens, and APL printers.

   The advent of Unicode has soved the last two problems rather
eleqantly: the Uncode character set contains all APL characters, and
screens (i.e CRT tubes in the old days and screen windows these days)
and printers display them properly.  What remains is the keyboard
problem.  The keyboard problem has two sub-problems: Keyboard caps that
show APL symbols in addition to the normal ASCII characters, and
generating proiper Unicodes when the keys are being pressed (typically
with the ALT or CTRL keys held down).

   GNU APL provides the debug command ]KEYB to help resolving these
issues.  There are two cases where ]KEYB may be useful:

   вҖў One can buy so called вҖҷAPL keyboardsвҖҷ or APL stickers that can be
     glued on the key caps of a regular keyboard.  As a matter of fact,
     APL keyboards are simply regular keyboards with differen key caps.
     The keycodes sent by APL keyboards do not differ from the keycodes
     of regular keyboards.  One the other hand, many programmers type
     blindly; for them the keycaps are mostly irrelevant, and the
     substantial surcharge for APL keyboards may be unreasonable.  A
     related problem is national keyboards: most APL keyboards have a US
     layout for their keycaps although a user may prefer a national
     layout.  Most of this can be helped with a keuboard layout that is
     printed on the screen.  A user that types bindly most of the time,
     but cannot remember the position of all APL symbols (in particular
     of rarely used ones) may find it useful to display the keyboard
     layout on the screen.

   вҖў The other use case for ]KEYB is troubleshooting the transformation
     of keys pressed on the keyboard to Unicodes sent to the APL
     interpreter.  This transformation (which is explained in more
     detail below) is highly conficurable.  The good news is that these
     days any keyboard can be configured to send any Unicode on any key
     as preferered by the user.  The bad news is that this configuration
     differs a lot between different platforms and can be faily
     cumbersome.  The ]KEYB command is intended to help figuring why
     pressing a partiicular key does not produce the APL character that
     it should.  It maybe wothwhile to note that even an APL keyboard
     can (and most likely will) not produce the characters shown on its
     keypad if the transformation from key presses to Unicdes is
     misconfigured.  In that respect APL keyboards are no better than
     keybiard stickers: Glueing a вҚҙ sticker onto the R does not make the
     R send the Unicode for вҚҙ.  Likewise, an APL keyboard with вҚҙ printed
     in addition to R does not make that keyboard send the Unicode for
     вҚҙ.  Both cases only work as expected if the transformation from
     keys to Unicdes is configured properly.

* Menu:

* The transformation of Keycodes to Unicodes::
* xmodmap and friends::
* The ]KEYB command::


File: apl.info,  Node: The transformation of Keycodes to Unicodes,  Next: xmodmap and friends,  Up: ]KEYB Command

2.11.1 The transformation of Keycodes to Unicodes
-------------------------------------------------

In a nutshell, on a GNU/Linux (or other X-based) platform, a key pressed
or realeased is processed as follows:

  1. The user presses or releases a key on the keyboard.  This creates a
     key-event in the operating system.  This key-event contains three
     items:
        вҖў a keycode which is a number between 0 and 255 that uniquely
          identidies the key.  The keys in the main keyboard area (i.e.
          where all the alkphabetic keys are located), have keycodes
          between 8 and 64,
        вҖў a state which tells if the key was pressed or released, and
        вҖў a timestanp which tells when key was pressed or released.
  2. The operating system processes the event:
        вҖў It remembers the new state of the key.  If the key is a
          modifier key such as SHIFT, CTRL, or ALT, the the processing
          is done.
        вҖў Otherwise the key is a normal key and the operating system
          computes a keysymbol from the keycode.  In this computation
          the modifier keys whose states were remembered in the previous
          steps are taken into account.  For that reason, e.g.  pressing
          R when (only) the SHIFT modifier key is pressed produces R and
          if SHIFT is released then it produces r.  Every Unicode has a
          keysymbol (with the same value) but some keysymbols doe not
          correspond to a Unicode but o an action that the oprating
          system shall perform (e.g.  cursor home in a termina window).
          A particularly important keysymbol is 0x0000 aka.  NoSymbol
          which indicates that (for a given combination of modifer keys)
          no Unicode shall be generated.

  3. The operating system forwards the keysymbol towards the application
     (in our case GNU APL). On the way from the operating system to the
     application there may be other mappings applied to the keysymbol.
     For example, the window manager may bind functions to function the
     keys of the keyboard and call the function when the keysymbol for
     the function key was received from the operating system.  Every
     such mapping can be a cause of trouble if keys needed by GNU APL
     are involved.


File: apl.info,  Node: xmodmap and friends,  Next: The ]KEYB command,  Prev: The transformation of Keycodes to Unicodes,  Up: ]KEYB Command

2.11.2 xmodmap and friends
--------------------------

The installation of an operating system installs a Keycodes to Unicodes
mapping according to the language choices made by the user during the
installation.  for example, in the US keycode 29 will be mapped to y,
while in Germany keycode 29 will be mapped to z.  At this point most
mappings for modifier ALT pressed, and most settings for CTRL pressed
are set to NoSymbol so that pressing these keys together with CTRL or
ALT have no effect.  To generate APL characteres instead of nothing, the
user has to modify the mapping as to produce APL Unicodes.  This
modification is lost after rebooting the computer; therefore the mapping
is usually performed in a script that is run at login time of the user
(i.e.  in ~/.bashrc).

   The modification is made with a program.  Unfortunately there exist
several such programs, e.g.  xmodmap, setxkbmap, or loadkeys.  See
README-3-keyboard for details.  More is not always better and the
different programs for the same purpose have undesirable side effects
when used in parallel.  An important lesson after experimenting with
several of these programs was: Use one and only one of these programs on
your platform.

   Each of these programs has its own set of pitfalls.  For example with
xmodmap, pressing ALT-SHIFT-L (in that order produces вҢ·.  Pressing
SHIFT-ALT-L produces nothing.

   Despite of this, xmodmap seems to be the simplest and most reliable
of the modidication programs.  It may have less capabilities than the
others, but has everything needed to run GNU APL. For this reason, GNU
APL is shipped with a configuration file for US keyboards
(support-files/Juergen-Mint-21/xmodmap.apl) and a file to undo the
mapping (support-files/Juergen-Mint-21/xmodmap.ascii).  The latter is
redundant since xmodmap provides a way to save the current mapping (see
man xmodmap).  There was a short period where xmodmap did not work in
Linux Mint several yeras ago, but this has been fixed in the meantime.

   It is impossible for the author to explain all available mapping
programs and therefore this manual focuses on xmodmap and, as an
alternative, setxkbmap/xkbcomp.  xmodmap is considerably simpler to
configure than setxkbmap/xkbcomp but not available on all platforms.

   Suppose we run:

   $ xmodmap xmodmap.apl

   and suppose pressing key R does not produce вҚҙ.  This can have the
following reasons:

  1. incorrect keycode for key R,
  2. correct keycode, but incorrect keysymbol(s), or

   Both cases can be identified with the ]KEYB command.


