2.11.3.1 ]KEYB Syntax
.....................

The syntax of the ]KEYB command is:

           ]KEYB [mode] [arguments]

   where the optional mode determines how the output shall be generated,
and the optional arguments specify additional details for the output.
There are 3 different modes:

   вҖў Mode XMOD uses the program xmodmap to figure the keyboard layout.
     This mode, if it works, produces an output that is closest to
     reality.
   вҖў Mode XKBD uses the X extension Xkbd which is typically configured
     with the programs setxkbmap and xkbcomp.  GNU APL reads the result
     of that configuration back with function XkbKeycodeToKeysym.  This
     mode, if it works, produces an output that is also closest to
     reality.
   вҖў Mode USER display a keyboard layout provided by the user.  The
     output of this mode is as correct as its input.
   вҖў mode GUESS displays a typical APL keyboard layout (which may differ
     considerably from the true keyboard layout).

   WARNING: In theory one could map some keys with xmodmap and others
with xkbcomp.  Even though one might be able to achieve a desired
mapping in this way (and maybe quicker than with either of the methods
alone), ]KEYB will not be able to display it properly.  This is because
the xmodmap -pke does not see the xkbcomp mapping and the X function
XkbKeycodeToKeysym() does not see the xmodmap mapping.


File: apl.info,  Node: ]KEYB without a mode,  Next: ]KEYB XMOD,  Prev: ]KEYB Syntax,  Up: The ]KEYB command

2.11.3.2 ]KEYB without a mode
.............................

Command i]KEYB without a mode is for the normal day to day use (as
opposed to troubleshooting).  It displays an APL keyboard on the screen,
which is very useful if the keyboard has no APL stickers or key caps.

   ]KEYB without a mode tries (in that order):

  1. ]KEYB XMOD
  2. ]KEYB USER
  3. ]KEYB GUESS

   The command stops after the first mode that was successful.  Mode
GUESS always succeeds, therefore ]KEYB will always produce an output.
If that output is correct is a different question, though.

   The first line of the keyboard displayed shows which of the 3 methods
above was used to generate the output.

   As may have become clear from the explanations above and/or from
reading README-3-keyboard in the top-level GNU APL directory, ]KEYB XMOD
will fail if either xmodmap is not used at all, or if xmodmap is
combined with other keyboard mapping programs.  For these cases, the
user can disable the automatic use of xmodmap in one of her preferences
files.  The option to do so is NO-XMODMAP and ii is effective only of
]KEYB is calle without a mode.  That is, ]KEYB XMOD will use xmodmap
even if xmodmap was disabled by NO-XMODMAP in a preferences file.


File: apl.info,  Node: ]KEYB XMOD,  Next: ]KEYB USER,  Prev: ]KEYB without a mode,  Up: The ]KEYB command

2.11.3.3 ]KEYB XMOD
...................

]KEYB XMOD runs, under the hood, xmodmap -pke to read the current
keycode to keysymbol mapping and displays the result in form of a
keyboard layout on the screen.  For example:

