2.19 Monadic вҠў and вҠЈ; dyadic вҠў with Axis
========================================

Monadic вҠў is the identity function.  It returns its (committed or
non-committed) right argument as a non-committed value.

   Conversely, monadic вҠЈ (called Hide in GNU APL) discards its
(committed or non-committed) right argument and returns a committed
integer scalar 0.

   For the most part there is no difference between a committed value (=
a value that was assigned to a variable, including вҺ• and вҚһ) and a
non-committed value.  The point where it does make a difference is when
the value is the final result of a statement (as opposed to an
intermediate result inside a statement).  In that situation (and only
there) a non-committed value is printed but a committed value is not.

   You can use вҠў in a similar fashion as вҺ•вҶҗ at the left end of a
statement, to print a value even though it was previously assigned to a
variable.

   The main motivation for вҠЈ is that, at least in GNU APL, lambdas
always return a value.  However, if a lambda is used only for the sake
of its side effects, say to print something, then the value returned by
the lambda is often of no interest and only messes up the APL output.
In that situation вҠЈ can be used to suppress the printing of undesired
return values from lambdas.

   In earlier GNU APL versions, вҠЈB and вҠўB would both return B; with вҠЈ as
committed value and with вҠў as non-committed value.  But since the only
real-life purpose of вҠЈ is to suppress the printing of B, the
implementation of вҠЈ was changed to returning a committed integer scalar
0 instead of committed B. That reduced the run-time of вҠЈB from O(,B) to
O(1).  Also, вҠўB is marginally faster than вҺ•вҶҗB.

   Dyadic вҠў with axis is a selection function that generalizes вҠЈ and вҠў.

   Let ZвҶҗA вҠў[X] B. Then:

   вҖў if X is a one-element vector and вҶ‘X is 0 then Z вүЎ A,
   вҖў if X is a one-element vector and вҶ‘X is 1 then Z вүЎ B,
   вҖў otherwise X selects items of A or B if the corresponding elements
     of X are 0 or 1 respectively.  In that case, the shapes of A and B
     must match the shape of X, but one-element A or B are scalar
     extended to the shape of X.

   Example:
           AвҶҗ2 3вҚҙ'abcdef'
           BвҶҗ2 3вҚҙвҚі6
           XвҶҗ2 3вҚҙ0 1 0 1 0 1
           A вҠў[X] B
     a 2 c
     4 e 6

        A вҠў[X] '*'
     a*c
     *e*

       '*' вҠў[X] B
     * 2 *
     4 * 6


