2.21 вҠӨ (Encode) with Axis
=========================

The dyadic primitive function A вҠҘ B (Decode) computes the values of B in
a number system with radices A. The most common case is a homogeneous
radix, i.e.  all items of A are the same.  In that case the radix A can
be specified as a scalar A which will be scalar-extended to the length
of B (more precisely: to вҶ‘вҚҙB). For example:

           2 2 2 2 вҠҘ 1 1 0 1
     13

           2вҠҘ1 1 0 1              вҚқ scalar extension of 2 to length 4
     13

           ((вҚҙB)вҚҙ2) вҠӨ BвҶҗ1 1 0 1   вҚқ scalar extension of 2 to вҶ‘вҚҙB
     13

   The dyadic primitive function A вҠӨ B (Encode) computes the
representation of B in a number system whose radices are A. The most
common case is again a homogeneous radix A. In this sense, Encode is the
inverse function of Decode.  Unfortunately Encode can not scalar extend
the radix A. This is because the shapes of its arguments do not provide
sufficient information to determine the radix length that shall be used.
As a consequence:

   вҖў the user needs to provide the radix A as a vector with identical
     items and with a length that is suitable for the items in B,
   вҖў if more radix items than needed are provided, then the result
     contains leading 0s (which is sort of OK because no information is
     lost), but
   вҖў if less radix items than needed are provided, then an oberflow
     occurs and the result is truncated.  This is awkward because, for
     example

                2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 вҠӨ 1000     вҚқ radix too short for 1000
          1 1 1 0 1 0 0 0

                2 вҠҘ 1 1 1 0 1 0 0 0        вҚқ therefore not 1000 !!!
          232
                232 + (2вӢҶ8) + (2вӢҶ9)        вҚқ add missing items
          1000

   вҖў The IBM APL2 language reference manual proposes to use the APL
     expression вҢҠ1вҲЈ+AвҚҹ(вҲЈB)+A=0 for the optimal length of the radix A.

   We call a radix length вҚҙA optimal if it is neither too long nor to
short.  In that case the result has no leading zeros and B вүЎ AвҠҘAвҠӨN. For
an optimal radix length are AвҠӨ and AвҠҘ the inverse functions of each
other.

   In order to improve on this, GNU APL offers the possibility to
automatically (and without using AвҚҹB) compute the optimal radix length
from A and B. The solution implemented in GNU APL is to provide the
optimal radix length as an axis argument.  There are two different cases
for the axis argument:

   вҖў If the optimal radix length is known, say N > 0, then the radix
     length is given as axis argument N>0.  In this case the left
     argument of AвҠӨB is slightly simplified:

                (NвҚҙвҶ‘A) вҠӨ B   вҶҗвҶ’   A вҠӨ[N] B   вҚқ optimal radix length N>0 is known

     This case frequently occurs when integer(s) B are encoded into
     hexadecimal 8-bit (i.e.  radix length = 2 hex digits), 16-bit words
     (i.e.  radix length = 4 hex digits), 32-bit longs (i.e.  radix
     length = 8 hex digits), or 64-bit long longs (i.e.  radix length =
     16 hex digits).

   вҖў Otherwise the radix length is not known; this case is specified as
     axis argument 0.  This is also the case where вҢҠ1вҲЈ+AвҚҹ(вҲЈB)+A=0 would
     be needed, and it simplifies AвҠӨB considerably:

                ((вҢҠ1вҲЈ+AвҚҹ(вҲЈB)+A=0)вҚҙвҶ‘A) вҠӨ B   вҶҗвҶ’   A вҠӨ [0]B   вҚқ unknown radix length

   Please note the following:

   вҖў Obviously the case N>0 is faster than the case N=0 because the user
     has taken over radix length computation.  However, AвҠӨ[N]B is still
     faster than the classical (NвҚҙвҶ‘A)вҠӨB.

   вҖў If all items in B are non-negative, then the case N=0 uses the
     optimal radix length for unsigned numbers, i.e.  without a sign.
     The result can be used in what is known as unsigned base-A
     arithmetic.

   вҖў If some item of B is negative, then the case N=0 uses a radix
     length that includes a sign (aka.  twoвҖҷs complement arithmetic if
     A=2).  The sign is 0 for the non-negative items of B and A-1 for
     the negative items of B (= 1 for binary encodings).

   Examples:
           2вҠӨ[4] 13           вҚқ 4 digit radix, positive B
     1 1 0 1

           2вҠҘ1 1 0 1          вҚқ proof
     13

           2вҠӨ[5] ВҜ13          вҚқ 5 digit radix, negative B
     1 0 0 1 1

           32 - 2вҠҘ1 0 0 1 1   вҚқ proof
     13



