2.23.1 вҢ№[1] and вҢ№[2] - QR Factorizations
----------------------------------------

ZвҶҗвҢ№[1] B and ZвҶҗвҢ№[2] B compute a QR factorization of the real or complex
matrix B. The results of ZвҶҗвҢ№[1] B and ZвҶҗвҢ№[2] B are conceptually
identical, while the algorithms used to compute the results differ.
Also, ZвҶҗвҢ№[1] B always exist, while ZвҶҗвҢ№[2] B requires libgsl to be
installed when GNU APL is compiled.

   The axis argument X is used to either clear near-0 matrix items to
exactly 0.0 during the computation (in Garry HelzerвҖҷs algorithm), or
else to select a different algorithm for computing the factorization.
Set XвҶҗвҺ•CT if unsure.

   The result Z is a triple (Q R Ri)вҶҗZ with the following properties.
Let вҚҙB=(M, N).

   * Q is an orthogonal MГ—M matrix, i.e Q^{-1} = Q^{T}, and Q +.Г— вҚүQ is
the MГ—M identity matrix I_{M} (with I_{M}вҶҗвҲҳ.=вҚЁвҚіM).

   * R is an upper triangular NГ—N matrix, i.e.  R[m;n] = 0 for all n <
m.  Note that if M>N then, following a convention in other libraries
(read: libgsl), the triangular matrices R and Ri have shape (N N) and
not (M N). This is because the rows below row N are always 0 in R and in
Ri, and are therefore not of interest.  As a consequence, in order to
restore B from Q and R one has to either use Q+.Г—M NвҶ‘R or else QвҲҳR (the
latter accepts arguments R with fewer rows than columns of Q.

   * Ri is the inverse of R, i.e.  Ri +.Г— R is the NГ—N identity matrix
I_{N}.

   * B = Q +.Г— M NвҶ‘R.

