2.25 Dyadic вҺ•CR
===============

The вҺ•CR function has now an optional left argument that selects one of
several formatting styles and conversion functions in addition to the
well-known monadic form.

   Calling вҺ•CR monadically without an axis and with an empty right
argument shows a list of all functions provided by вҺ•CR:

           вҺ•CR ''

   Definition: A byte vector is an integer (!)  vector with numbers
having a (signed or unsigned) 8-bit value (i.e.  a value from -128 to
255 inclusive).  Such byte vectors are frequently used arguments and
results of вҺ•FIO functions.

   Let ZвҶҗA вҺ•CR B.

   Then the left argument A of вҺ•CR selects one of several sub-functions
of вҺ•CR:

   вҖў AвҲҲ0 1 2 3 4 7 8 9 29: various formatting styles (boxed, APL
     input/output, etc.).  Just try them out.

   вҖў AвҲҲ5 6: convert byte vector B to a string of uppercase or lowercase
     i hex digits respectively.  Every byte in B becomes 2 characters in
     Z.

   вҖў A=10: convert variable named in B to an APL expression producing
     it.

   вҖў A=11: convert value B to byte vector Z in CDR ("Common Data
     Representation", an IBM standard) format (similar to 3 вҺ•TF).

   вҖў A=12: convert byte vector B in CDR format to value Z.

   вҖў A=13: convert hex string B to byte vector Z.

     If a conversion has an inverse conversion (like 12 being the
     inverse of 11) then the inverse conversion can be expressed as the
     negative of the conversion number.  For example, 12 вҺ•CR B is the
     same as ВҜ11 вҺ•CR B.

   вҖў A=14: conversion 11 followed by conversion 13 (Value to hex string
     in CDR format)

   вҖў A=15: conversion 13 followed by conversion 12 (hex string in CDR
     format to Value)

   вҖў A=16: encode byte vector B into Z (base64 encoding, RFC 4648)

   вҖў A=17: decode base64 vector B into byte vector Z (base64 encoding,
     RFC 4648)

   вҖў A=18: convert text vector B into byte vector Z (UTF8 encoding, RFC
     3629)

   вҖў A=19: convert byte vector B into text vector Z (UTF8 encoding, RFC
     3629)

   вҖў A=20-25: like 3,4,i or 7-9 but using a formatting similar to NARS
     APL вҺ•FMT (showing the axis lengths as numbers instead of вҶ’ and вҶ“)

   вҖў A=26: Z is the cell types of the ravel elements of B, i.e.
        вҖў 2: character,
        вҖў 16: integer,
        вҖў 32: real number,
        вҖў 64: complex number.

   вҖў A=27: Z[I] is the primary data representation (for example the real
     part of a complex number, or the numerator of a rational number) of
     B[I].

   вҖў A=28: Z[I] is the additional data representation (for example the
     imaginary part of a complex number, or the denominator of a
     rational number) of B[I].

   вҖў A=30: Z is B with all top-level elements conformed to a common rank
     and shape (as required by the вҚӨ operator).  This conversion is
     primarily used internally by the GNU APL interpreter.

   вҖў AвҲҲ31 32: These conversions are used internally by вҺ•INP.

   вҖў A=33: convert tagged byte vector to a TLV (Tag/Length/Value)
     buffer.  The TLV buffer can be sent over a byte stream (socket) and
     easily decoded at the other end.  Say B = B[1], B[2], ..., B[n]
     such that B1 is an Integer (the tag) and B[j] is a character in the
     range 0-255 for j > 1.  Let ZвҶҗ33 вҺ•CR B with Z = Z[1], Z[2], ...
     Z[m].  Then Z[1 2 3 4] is the 4 byte tag, Z[5 6 7 8] is the 4 byte
     data length (n-1) = (m - 8), and 1вҶ“B == 8 вҶ“ Z. In other words, the
     first 4 bytes of Z are the tag in big endian byte order, the next 4
     bytes are the length of B except the tag, and the rest of Z is B
     except the tag.

     Example:
                TagвҶҗ55   вҚқ hex 37
                5 вҺ•CR 33 вҺ•CR Tag,'Value'
          000000370000000556616C7565

   вҖў A=34: this is the inverse of 33 вҺ•CR. The intended use for 33 вҺ•CR
     and 34 вҺ•CR is the transmission of a tagged byte vector over e.g a
     TCP socket:

       Sender                                              Receiver
       в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ                                              в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ
       T,Data вҶ’вҶ’вҶ’ 33 вҺ•CR T,Data   вҶ’вҶ’вҶ’ TCP connection вҶ’вҶ’вҶ’   34 вҺ•CR T,Data вҶ’вҶ’вҶ’ T,Data

     Example:
                34 вҺ•CR ВҜ5 вҺ•CR '000000370000000556616C7565'
          55 Value

     The TLVs constructed by 33 вҺ•CR by the sender and decoded with 34
     вҺ•CR by the receiver can be sent back-to-back over a TCP connection
     or similar in such a way that the receiver knows exactly after
     which byte a TLV ends (and possibly the next TLV, if any, starts).
     This is perfect for connections over which data is sent
     sporadically.  33 вҺ•CR and 34 вҺ•CR are particularly useful for
     encoding and decoding TLV byte buffers exchanged between GNU APL
     and processes that were forked by GNU APL with вҺ•FIO[57] (aka.
     fork() and execve()).

   вҖў A=35: convert a string of lines (containing LF characters as line
     delimiters) to a nested vector of lines.

   вҖў A=36: the inverse of вҺ•CR[35].  Convert a nested vector of lines to
     a string with lines terminated with LF characxters.

   вҖў A=37: Same as вҺ•CR B but without removing any indentation.

   вҖў A=38: Return an empty structured variable with (integer) capacity
     Bi, or convert an NГ—2 matrix B to a structured variable.

   вҖў A=39: convert a strucured variable B to an NГ—2 variable.

   вҖў A=40: pack a boolean variable Bi (experimental).

   вҖў A=41: unpack a boolean variable Bi (experimental).

   вҖў A=42: tokenize the APL statement Bs.

   вҖў A=43: parse the APL statement Bs.

   вҖў A=44: decode the (integer) token tag B or the (nested) token B.

   Most dyadic вҺ•CR variants whose argument B is expected to be a byte
vector throw:

   вҖў RANK ERROR if 1вү вҚҙвҚҙB
   вҖў DOMAIN ERROR if one of the B[j] is not a proper byte value

   A proper byte value is either an integer in the range -128...255
inclusive, or a (Unicode) character with a code point between U+FF80 and
U+FFFF (inclusive, corresponding to a negative signed char in C/C++) or
between U+0000...U+00FF (inclusive, corresponding to an unsigned char or
to a signed positive char in C/C++).  Real, Complex, or rational numbers
are never proper byte values even if their value is close to an integer.
Nor are nested APL values or values being assigned.

   вҺ•CR is a function group, therefore its sub-functions can be selected
with a name.  For example: monadic вҺ•CR.hex_to_bytes is the same as
monadic вҺ•CR[13] or dyadic 13 вҺ•CR.


