2.35.4 Eigenvector
------------------

The eigenvector operation, вҺ•MX[4], is monadic and returns the complex
eigenvectors of real non-symetric square matrices:

           B
     ВҜ1  1 ВҜ1 1
     ВҜ8  4 ВҜ2 1
     27  9  3 1
     64 16  4 1
           вҺ•PPвҶҗ4
           вҺ•MX[4] B
       0.09988            0.1113          ВҜ0.2925          ВҜ0.9445
       0.04308J0.009687  ВҜ0.07091J0.1389   0.5166JВҜ0.01601  0.8396J0.04139
       0.04308JВҜ0.009687 ВҜ0.07091JВҜ0.1389  0.5166J0.01601   0.8396JВҜ0.04139
      ВҜ0.1449             0.3566           0.9194           0.08118

   where each row represents an eigenvector:

           EвҶҗвҺ•MX[4] B
           E[вҺ•IO;]                   вҚқ first vector
     0.09988 0.1113 ВҜ0.2925 ВҜ0.9445
           E[вҺ•IO+1;]                 вҚқ second vector
     0.04308J0.009687 ВҜ0.07091J0.1389 0.5166JВҜ0.01601 0.8396J0.04139
           etc.

   The eigenvalues are computed concurrently and the eignenvector matrix
is sorted according to the descending magnitude of the corresponding
eigenvalues.


File: apl.info,  Node: Eigenvalue,  Next: Ident,  Prev: Eigenvector,  Up: вҺ•MX - Matrix/Statistics

2.35.5 Eigenvalue
-----------------

The eigenvalue operation, вҺ•MX[5], is also monadic with an argument of
the same shape as that of the argument of the eigenvector operation.  It
returns a sorted complex vector of eigenvalues of the matrix argument:

           вҠўFвҶҗвҺ•MX[5] B
     ВҜ6.414 5.546J3.085 5.546JВҜ3.085 2.323

   The order of eigen vectors, E from above, is related to the order of
the eigenvalues, F, by the relationship:

                  E[k;] в¬„ F[k]

   (Note that, from the above example:

           |F
     6.41391 6.346285607 6.346285607 2.3228

   the order of the magnitude of the elements is descending, making the
initial eigenvector, E[вҺ•IO;], the dominant eigenvector and each
successive eigenvector successively less significant.)

   Accordingly:

           4 вҺ•CR (вҠӮвҚү(1,вҚҙF)вҚҙF),(вҠӮE)
