2.36.5 GUI driver
-----------------

вҺ•PLOT provides 3 different ways to generate its output, called GUI
drivers.  Two of these drivers (GTK and XCB) are optional, while third
third driver ASCII is not.  Optional means that the ./configure script,
which is executed as the first step in the compilation of GNU APL,
determines if the prerequisite for an optional driver are satisfied.
IOW an optional driver is only available for вҺ•PLOT if the libraries and
C/C++ header files needed to compile the driver are installed at the
time where GNU APL is being compiled.  The ASCII driver merely generates
ESC squences for VT100 terminals and does therefore not depend on
additional libraries.

   For the monadic вҺ•PLOT B, the driver used by вҺ•PLOT is chosen as
follows:

   вҖў GTK if available, otherwise
   вҖў XCB if available, otherwise
   вҖў ASCII

   For the dyadic A вҺ•PLOT B, the driver used is the same, but the choice
made by ./configure can be overridden by the plot window attribute
gui_driver.  The default for this plot window attribute is empty, which
means that the decision of ./configure shall be used (like in the
monadic case where no plot attributes can be specified).

   The plot driver also affects the type of result returned by вҺ•PLOT:

   вҖў drivers GTK and XCB return an integer scalar H (a plot window
     handle) that can later be used from APL to programmatically close
     the plot window (i.e.  with вҺ•PLOT H) with that handle.
     (Alternatively a GTK or XCB plot window can be closed by clicking
     the close button of the plot window).

   вҖў driver ASCII returns a 3-dimensional APL value Z, where:
        вҖў Z[1;;] is a character matrix with the Unicode characters used
          to draw the plot window,
        вҖў Z[2;;] is an integer matrix with the the forground colors (in
          terms of VT100 terminal colors), and
        вҖў Z[3;;] is an integer matrix with the the backround colors
          (again in terms of VT100 terminal colors).

   The VT100 colors returnd by the ASCII driver are essentially 4-bit
RGB values with the following integer encoding:

   вҖў 0 = 0b000: (dark) black,
   вҖў 1 = 0b001: (dark) red,
   вҖў 2 = 0b010: (dark) green,
   вҖў 3 = 0b011: (dark) yellow,
   вҖў 4 = 0b100: (dark) blue,
   вҖў 5 = 0b101: (dark) magenta,
   вҖў 6 = 0b110: (dark) cyan,
   вҖў 7 = 0b111: (dark) white (kind of grey),
   вҖў 60 = 60 + 0b000: bright black (another kind of grey),
   вҖў 61 = 60 + 0b001: bright red,
   вҖў 62 = 60 + 0b010: bright green,
   вҖў 63 = 60 + 0b011: bright yellow,
   вҖў 64 = 60 + 0b100: bright blue,
   вҖў 65 = 60 + 0b101: bright magenta,
   вҖў 66 = 60 + 0b110: bright cyan, and
   вҖў 67 = 60 + 0b111: bright white

   The ASCII driver returns its result as a committed value (so that the
plot window is not drawn twice if the value is not assigned to a
variable).  Naturally the ASCII driver can not support most of the вҺ•PLOT
atrributes like a true graphical driver like GTK or XCB. But at least
the color attributes are honored by rounding 3Г—8-bit RGB values to their
nearest 4-bit VT100 color.

   Some terminal emulators have issues when characters are printed on
the last column of the terminal.  This is addressed by a user preference
named plot-ASCII-columns, which should be set to one less the number of
columns of the terminal (so that the last columns in not written).

   Another preferencefor the ASCII driver that might be of interest is
plot-ASCII-background.  It sets the background color for the terminal if
the Plot attribute canvas-color is not provided (e.g.  in monadic вҺ•PLOT
which has no plot attributes).

   The XCB driver was the first driver for вҺ•PLOT but has since become
somewhat obsolete.  It has limitation when it comes to the display of
texts (in particular for APL characters).  The long-term GNU APL design
strategy is therefore GTK in favor of the good old XCB. XCB will still
be supported for a while, but new features will only be added to the GTK
driver.


