2.42.14.2 Creating a new Database
.................................

To read from or write into a database we need a database handle
(sometimes called a database connection) for it:

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           вҚқ create a new (and empty) database
           вҚқ
           Filename вҶҗ 'db.sqlite'            вҚқ name of the database to be created
           Type вҶҗ 'sqlite'                   вҚқ database type
           DB вҶҗ Type вҺ•SQL.open Filename      вҚқ create the database

           вҺ•SQL.close DB                     вҚқ and close it

   NOTES: If a file with the given Filename already exists, then
вҺ•SQL.open simply connects to it and returns a handle (a small integer)
for the connection.  The handle is used like a file descri[tor for an
open file in the operating system.  The handle is later used for
subsequent database operations of вҺ•SQL (until the connection is closed).

   If no file with the given Filename exists, then вҺ•SQL.open creates a
file with than name and then connects to it.  It is possible to have
several such connections to different databases at the same time.  It is
also possible to have several connections to the same database at the
same time (and then one should use database transactions to avoid
conflicts with the data written to the same database via different
connections).

   postgreSQL is shipped with programs createdb for creating databases,
createuser for creating database users, and psql for various other
database administration tasks.  These programs can be called from APL
with the )HOST command or with вҺ•FIO.fork_daemon.


File: apl.info,  Node: Creating a Database Table,  Next: Excursus: Dynamic Query Strings,  Prev: Creating a new Database,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.3 Creating a Database Table
...................................

An SQL database is a set of tables.  The next step after a new database
was created and a connection to it was opened is to define one or more
tables in the database.  Every table has one or more named columns and
zero or more rows.  Every column has attributes, some of which are
mandatory (e.g.  the column name and in some SQL dialects the data type)
while others are optional (e.g.  the data type in other SQL dialects or
the size of the items in the column).  Creating a database table means
to specify a name for a table and to specify the attributes of the table
columns.

   In this quickstart we create a table named EMPLOYEES with 5 columns
named ID, NAME, ADDRESS, AGE, and SALARY.

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           Filename вҶҗ 'db.sqlite'            вҚқ name of the database to be used
           Type вҶҗ 'sqlite'                   вҚқ database type
           DB вҶҗ Type вҺ•SQL.open Filename      вҚқ open the database

           вҚқ define an SQL Query string Qs that creates a table
           вҚқ
           Qs вҶҗ ,вҠғВ«В«В«
           CREATE TABLE EMPLOYEES(
                  ID      INT  NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
                  NAME    TEXT NOT NULL,
                  AGE     INT  NOT NULL,
                  ADDRESS CHAR(50),
                  SALARY  REAL);
                  В»В»В»

           вҚқ perform the SQL query according to query string Qs.
           вҚқ
           Qs вҺ•SQL.query DB вҚ¬

           вҚқ show the tables in the database
           вҚқ
           вҺ•SQL.tables DB
      EMPLOYEES

           DB вҺ•SQL.columns 'EMPLOYEES'
      ID      INT
      NAME    TEXT
      AGE     INT
      ADDRESS CHAR(50)
      SALARY  REAL

           вҺ•SQL.close DB                     вҚқ and close DB

   NOTES: As we see above, SQL query strings tend to be quite long.  We
could have removed most of the blanks and all of the linefeeds in the
query string above, but readability of the SQL query would have suffered
a lot by doing that.  Instead we used a multi-line GNU APL script В«В«В«
...  В»В»В» for the query text, disclose it (which turns the APL vector of
strings into an APL matrix, and finally ravel it (to make it a string).

   Many SQL query strings contain strings themselves, e.g.  for column
names that contain blanks or for string values in columns.  IOW, the
query string is a string that contains other strings.  To avoid the need
to escape the SQL quotes inside (quoted) APL strings we have quoted the
multi-line query string with В«В«В« ...  В»В»В» instead of """ ...  """  or вҖқвҖҷ
...  вҖқвҖҷ.

   The right argument of вҺ•SQL.query is DB вҚ¬ (and not simply DB as in
other вҺ•SQL functions).  This is because an SQL query string can have
parameters as we will see below.  The query string above has no
parameters and therefore the parameter list for the query string is вҚ¬
aka.  вҚі0.

   Finally, SQL table columns have names, but SQL table rows do not.  It
is therefore common practice (though not required) that the first column
of a table is a unique integer ID that identifies the row and can later
be used to quickly locate the row in a large database.


File: apl.info,  Node: Excursus: Dynamic Query Strings,  Next: Writing an APL matrix into a Database Table,  Prev: Creating a Database Table,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.4 Excursus: Dynamic Query Strings
.........................................

The SQL query strings (Qs) used so far were static, which means that
they are sent verbatim to the database machinery.  In the following we
will also use SQL query strings that are are a mix of static text and
the character % in the query string.  In other SQL dialects the
placeholders may be different.  For example in postgreSQL the
placeholders in a query string are $1, $2, $3, and so forth.

   The placeholders in a dynamic query string are replaced by string is
to the database machinery.  For example:

           вҚқ dynamic query string Qs
           вҚқ
           Qs вҶҗ ,вҠғВ«В«В«
           INSERT INTO EMPLOYEES(ID, NAME, AGE, ADDRESS, SALARY
                    VALUES(?,  ?,    ?,   ?,       ?);
                В»В»В»

           вҚқ query string parameters
           вҚқ
           PARAMS вҶҗ 1 "Paul" 32 "California" 20000

           вҚқ number of placeholders in Qs
           вҚқ
           +/Qs = '?'
     5

           вҚқ number of parameters (shall be equal to the number of placeholders)
           вҚқ
           вҚҙPARAMS
     5

           вҚқ the (intermediate) result of replacing the placeholders in the dynamic
           вҚқ query string Qs would then be this static query string:
           вҚқ
           RESULT вҶҗ ,вҠғВ«В«В«
           INSERT INTO EMPLOYEES(ID, NAME, AGE, ADDRESS, SALARY
                    VALUES(1, "Paul", 32, "California", 20000);
                      В»В»В»

   The example above shows the binding of query string parameters to
query strings for the case where the rank of the parameters is вүӨ 1.
вҺ•SQL also supports parameters with rank 2; in that case the query is
repeated for every row of the parameter matrix.  I.e.  the placeholders
in same query string Qs are being replaced with every row of the
parameter matrix before the result of each replacement is sent as a
(static) query to the database machinery.  This feature makes it rather
simple to write an APL matrix (= query parameter) to the database.

   Dynamic query strings are allowed in two вҺ•SQL sub-functions: in
function 3 (вҺ•SQL.query) and in function 4 (вҺ•SQL.update).  The syntax
differs slightly beween вҺ•SQL function numbers and вҺ•SQL function names:

           Qs вҺ•SQL.query DB PARAMS       вҚқ вҺ•SQL sub-function name
           Qs вҺ•SQL[3, DB] PARAMS         вҚқ вҺ•SQL sub-function number

           Qs вҺ•SQL.update DB PARAMS      вҚқ вҺ•SQL sub-function name
           Qs вҺ•SQL[4, DB] PARAMS         вҚқ вҺ•SQL sub-function number

   For rank 2 parameters shall the number of placeholders be equal to
the number of colums of the APL matrix.  If a query string contains no
placeholders then the parameters shall be вҚ¬ (aka.  вҚі0).


File: apl.info,  Node: Writing an APL matrix into a Database Table,  Next: Reading a Database Table into an APL Matrix,  Prev: Excursus: Dynamic Query Strings,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.5 Writing an APL matrix into a Database Table
.....................................................

Now suppose that we have an APL matrix with the same columns as our SQL
table created above.

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           MATRIX вҶҗ 4 5вҚҙ0
           MATRIX[1;] вҶҗ 1 'Paul'   32 'California' 20000.00
           MATRIX[2;] вҶҗ 2 'Allan'  25 'Texas'      15000.00
           MATRIX[3;] вҶҗ 3 'Teddy'  23 'Norway'     20000.00
           MATRIX[4;] вҶҗ 4 'Gunnar' 26 'Sweden'     18000.00

           вҚқ show MATRXIX
           вҚқ
           8 вҺ•CR MATRIX
     в”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ
     вҶ“в”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ   32 в”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ 20000в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв”ӮPaulв”Ӯ      в”ӮCaliforniaв”Ӯ      в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ      в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ      в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ  25 в”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ      15000в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв”ӮAllanв”Ӯ     в”ӮTexasв”Ӯ           в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ     в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ           в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ  23 в”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ     20000в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв”ӮTeddyв”Ӯ     в”ӮNorwayв”Ӯ          в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ     в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ          в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ 26 в”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ     18000в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв”ӮGunnarв”Ӯ    в”ӮSwedenв”Ӯ          в”Ӯ
     в”Ӯв””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ    в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ          в”Ӯ
     в””Пөв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ

   This MATRIX can then be written (more precisely: appended) to the
database table EMPLOYEES like this:

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           Filename вҶҗ 'db.sqlite'            вҚқ name of the database to be used
           Type вҶҗ 'sqlite'                   вҚқ database type
           DB вҶҗ Type вҺ•SQL.open Filename      вҚқ open the database

           Qs вҶҗ ,вҠғВ«В«В«
           INSERT INTO EMPLOYEES(ID, NAME, AGE, ADDRESS, SALARY)
                          VALUES(?,  ?,    ?,   ?,       ?);
                В»В»В»
          Qs вҺ•SQL.query DB MATRIX

           вҺ•SQL.close DB                     вҚқ and close DB


File: apl.info,  Node: Reading a Database Table into an APL Matrix,  Next: Updating a Database Table,  Prev: Writing an APL matrix into a Database Table,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.6 Reading a Database Table into an APL Matrix
.....................................................

Reading a matrix back from a database table uses a SELECT query.  SELECT
is the counterpart of indexed reference or indexed assignment in APL and
works, like in APL, in both directions (i.e.  reading from tables and
writing to tables).  In a SELECT query one can select specific rows and
columns of the table, which is left as an exercise for the reader.  In
this quickstart we want to keep things simple and read an entire table
back:

   Due to the absence of a binding mechanism is reading back of an SQL
table into an APL matrix even simpler:

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           Filename вҶҗ 'db.sqlite'            вҚқ name of the database to be used
           Type вҶҗ 'sqlite'                   вҚқ database type
           DB вҶҗ Type вҺ•SQL.open Filename      вҚқ open the database

           Qs вҶҗ ,вҠғВ«В«В«
           SELECT * FROM EMPLOYEES;
                  В»В»В»

           RESULT вҶҗ Qs вҺ•SQL.query DB вҚ¬
           RESULT
      1 Paul   32 California 20000
      2 Allan  25 Texas      15000
      3 Teddy  23 Norway     20000
      4 Gunnar 26 Sweden     18000

           вҚҙRESULT
     4 5

           вҺ•SQL.close DB                     вҚқ and close DB

   NOTES: The * in the query string stands for all columns of the table.
* is NOT a placeholder because it is not replaced with a parameter.  One
can also retrieve a only subset of columns by using a comma separated
list of column names instead of * (similar to indexed reference in APL).


File: apl.info,  Node: Updating a Database Table,  Prev: Reading a Database Table into an APL Matrix,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.7 Updating a Database Table
...................................

The вҺ•SQL sub-function introduced so far suffice, at least in principle.
The APL programmer can read a table from the database into APL, analyse
and/or modify it in APL, and optionally write it back into the database.

   There is, however, one case where this approach becomes arbitrarily
inefficient: a large database with only a small change.  In that case it
is far more efficient to make a change directly in the database, i.e.
without transferring the entire database back and forth between APL and
SQL. This is achieved with an SQL UPDATE query, and вҺ•SQL.update does
exactly that.

   Suppose we want to increase TeddyвҖҷs salary from 20000 to 22000.
Then:

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           Filename вҶҗ 'db.sqlite'            вҚқ name of the database to be used
           Type вҶҗ 'sqlite'                   вҚқ database type
           DB вҶҗ Type вҺ•SQL.open Filename      вҚқ open the database

           Qs вҶҗ ,вҠғВ«В«В«
           UPDATE EMPLOYEES SET SALARY=? WHERE ID=?;
                  В»В»В»

           Qs вҺ•SQL.query DB (22000 3)        вҚқ update column SALARY in row 3

           вҚқ check result
           Qs вҶҗ ,вҠғВ«В«В«
           SELECT * FROM EMPLOYEES;
                  В»В»В»

           RESULT вҶҗ Qs вҺ•SQL.query DB вҚ¬
           RESULT
      1 Paul   32 California 20000
      2 Allan  25 Texas      15000
      3 Teddy  23 Norway     22000
      4 Gunnar 26 Sweden     18000

           вҚҙRESULT
     4 5

           вҺ•SQL.close DB                     вҚқ and close DB

   NOTES: an UPDATE query in SQL is pretty much what an indexed
assignment in APL. In the example above we changed a single column
SALARY in a single row ID in the database table COMPANY. The placeholder
% in SET SALARY=% was set to parameter 22000 and the place holder in
where ID=?  was set to TerryвҖҷs row with ID. Like in APL one can,
however, also change multiple rows and/or multiple columns in a database
table.  To change multiple columns one can set a comma separated list of
column names in the SET clause (or * for all columns).  For multiple
rows one can set multiple rows in the WHERE clause.  Omitting the WHERE
clause updates all rows (similar to * for columns) in the database.  For
example:

           UPDATE COMPANY SET AGE=?, SALARY=? WHERE ID IN (?, ?, ?);

   The shape of a parameter matrix for an SQL UPDATE must, of course,
match the number of selected rows and columns.


File: apl.info,  Node: Deleting Rows From a Database Table,  Prev: SQLite Quickstart,  Up: вҺ•SQL - SQL Database Interface

2.42.15 Deleting Rows From a Database Table
-------------------------------------------

Like UPDATE queries are efficient for changing large tables of a
database, there is also an SQL query for deleting one or more rows of a
database:

           QsвҶҗВ«DELETE FROM COMPANY WHERE ID=?;В»                вҚқ delete one row
           QsвҶҗВ«DELETE FROM COMPANY WHERE ID IN (?, ?, ?);В»     вҚқ delete 3 rows
           QsвҶҗВ«DELETE FROM COMPANY;В»                           вҚқ delete all (!) rows

           Qs вҺ•SQL.query DB B

   As usual, the number of rows must match the number of placeholders in
the query parameter B (an APL vector).


