2.45.2 Syntax
-------------

With the above considerations in mind, GNU APL decided in favor of the
following syntax for APL conditionals:

   вҖў one-sided if/else:
                COND вҶ’вҶ’ THEN-statement(s) вҶҗвҶҗ

   вҖў two-sided if/else:
                COND вҶ’вҶ’ THEN-statement(s) вҶҗвҶ’ ELSE-statement(s) вҶҗвҶҗ

   The following rules govern this syntax:

   вҖў The вҶ’вҶ’, вҶҗвҶ’, and вҶҗвҶҗ markers must be single tokens (2 adjacent
     Unicode characters).  No whitespace (and in particular no line
     feed) is permitted between the first and the second arrow.  A
     single вҶ’ is a valid APL statement (named Escape).  A linefeed
     between two вҶ’ turns the single token вҶ’вҶ’ into two valid (though most
     of the time useless) Escape statements.

   вҖў The COND, THEN, and ELSE clauses shall be sequences of valid APL
     statements.  In particular:
        вҖў The condition COND shall be a single statement that evaluates
          to a 1-item Boolean array (of any rank).  The statement result
          of COND is a committed value and is therefore not being
          displayed.

        вҖў The THEN clause shall be one or more valid statements,
          possibly separated by в—Ҡ for more than one statement.

        вҖў Likewise, the ELSE clause (if present) shall be one or more
          valid statements, separated by в—Ҡ for more than one statement.

   Examples:
           вҚқ short format. Valid in immediate execution and in defined functions
           вҚқ
           XвҶҗ5 в—Ҡ XвүҘ0 вҶ’вҶ’ X 'is positive' вҶҗвҶ’ X 'is negative' вҶҗвҶҗ
      5 is positive


           вҚқ long format. Only possible in defined functions because immediate
           вҚқ execution works line by line (and parsing the first line would fail).

           вҚқ valid split into several lines (in a defined function)
           вҚқ
           вҲҮFOO X
            XвүҘ0             вҶ’вҶ’
            X 'is positive' вҶҗвҶ’
            X 'is negative' вҶҗвҶҗ
           вҲҮ
           FOO 5
      5 is positive
           FOO ВҜ5
      ВҜ5 is negative


           вҚқ invalid split into several lines: вҶҗвҶ’ spread over 2 lines.
           вҚқ FOO can be properly parsed, but calling FOO fails.
           вҚқ
           вҲҮFOO X
           XвүҘ0 вҶ’вҶ’ X 'is positive' вҶҗ
                вҶ’ X 'is negative' вҶҗвҶҗ
           вҲҮ
           FOO 5
     SYNTAX ERROR+
     FOO[1]  X 'is positive'вҶҗ
             *              *

   The recommended usage of the corresponding вҶ’вҶ’, вҶҗвҶ’, and вҶҗвҶҗ token of
the same conditional is to:

   вҖў either put all of them on the same line (short format), or
   вҖў else align all of them on the same column (long form), but
   вҖў never mix the short and long forms

   In theory one could place (and align) the token before or after their
statement(s).  However, placing them after their statement(s), like
shown in the examples above, makes them arguably more visible and is
therefore the recommended way.  In particular when conditionals are
being nested.


File: apl.info,  Node: A Possible Pitfall,  Prev: Syntax,  Up: Conditionals

2.45.3 A Possible Pitfall
-------------------------

In APL, as well as in C/C++ (and most other languages), an expression is
also a statement, but not vice versa.  Expressions yield a value, while
statements may not.

   The C/C++ language knows conditional statements and conditional
expressions:

        if (COND) { IF-statements }       // conditional C/C++ statement
        else      { ELSE-statements }

        (COND) ? IF-value : ELSE-value    // conditional C/C++ expression

   Likewise, GNU APL also has conditional statements and conditional
expressions:

           COND вҶ’вҶ’ IF-statements вҶҗвҶ’ ELSE-statements вҶҗвҶҗ    вҚқ conditional APL statement

           IF-value вҠў[COND] ELSE-value                    вҚқ conditional APL expression

   If a value is needed, e.g.  for assigning it to a variable, but the
expression becomes too long to fit in a single line, then one can
replicate the assignment in both of the IF and the ELSE clauses:

           // C/C++
           x = -5;
           Result = (x < 0) ? "negative" : "positive";                          // OK
           Result = if (x < 0) { "negative"; } else { "positive"; }         // syntax error
           if (x < 0) { Result = "negative"; } else { Result = "positive"; }   // OK

           вҚқ GNU APL conditional expression, aka. вҠў[]
           XвҶҗВҜ5
           Result вҶҗ "positive" вҠў[X < 0] "negative"                     вҚқ OK
           Result вҶҗ (X < 0) вҶ’вҶ’ вҠЈ"negative" вҶҗвҶ’ вҠЈ"positive" вҶҗвҶҗ           вҚқ ???
           Result
     1

           (X < 0) вҶ’вҶ’ Result вҶҗ "negative" вҶҗвҶ’ Result вҶҗ "positive" вҶҗвҶҗ    вҚқ OK
           Result
     negative

   The correct, although possibly unexpected, result 1 of the APL
conditional in the line with comment вҚқ ???  above was evaluated as
follows:

  1. APL computes different statements from right to left.
  2. The conditional tokens вҶ’вҶ’, вҶҗвҶ’, and вҶҗвҶҗ are statement separators like
     в—Ҡ, but with the additional capability to jump over their THEN
     and/or ELSE clauses according to the value of their COND clause.
  3. The first statement in the example above is вҖҳResult вҶҗ (X < 0)вҖҷ i.e.
     вҖҳResultвҶҗ1вҖҷ.
  4. The statement result of COND is always a committed value,
     regardless of whether it is assigned to a variable (like in the
     example above) or not.  Therefore the COND clause does not produce
     any output.
  5. The next statement that is being executed it either вҖҳвҠЈ"negative"вҖҷ
     or else вҖҳвҠЈ"positive"вҖҷ, depending on the value of variable X.
     Normally it would be displayed, but due to вҠЈ the display is
     suppressed.  The entire conditional does therefore produce no
     output.
  6. As a consequence, вҖҳResult вҶҗ 1вҖҷ (and not, for example, вҖҳ"negative"вҖҷ
     !).
  7. The вҖҳвҠЈ"negative"вҖҷ and вҖҳвҠЈ"positive"вҖҷ are separate statements which
     do not assign anything to Result in the previous COND clause.  The
     pitfall in the example is that the conditional looks like it would
     assign either "negative" or "positive" to Result, but in fact
     assigns 1.

   Needless to say that, as in the example above, the assignment of a
APL conditional statement to a variable is, although possible, a dubious
programming style that should be avoided for the sake of readability.
The key takeaway here is that the clauses of a GNU APL conditional are
(two or three) different statements, and that an assignment of the
conditional to a variable assigns only the first of these statements to
the variable.

   In C/C++, the condition of a conditional statement MUST be put in
parentheses, while the condition of a conditional expression MAY be put
in parentheses.

   In GNU APL the condition of a conditional statement MAY be put in
parentheses, while the condition of conditional expression MUST be put
in brackets (since it is the axis argument X of A вҠў[X] B.. A good
programming practice in C/C++ and in GNU APL is to always put the
condition into parentheses even if that if not syntactically required.
Some people even use double parentheses to emphasize the condition of a
conditional statement or expression.


File: apl.info,  Node: Matrix Product,  Next: Monadic вү  (Nub Sieve),  Prev: Conditionals,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.46 Matrix Product
===================

In standard APL, the inner product Z of two matrices A and B as known
from linear algebra, is:

           ZвҶҗA +.Г— B      вҚқ the most frequent special case of A f.g B

   However, the inner product in APL is more general than the inner
product in linear algebra.  In the general case A f.g B may the
functions f and g also be non-scalar APL primitives or even defined
functions.  This generality may occasionally be helpful, but it comes
with a performance penalty since many argument checks are duplicated.
At the same time A +.Г— B is by far the most frequent use of the inner
product operator вҖҷ.вҖҷ.

   For this reason GNU APL also provides a slightly more efficient
dyadic function вҲҳ (Matrix Product) for the special case +.Г— of the
dyadic operator вҖҷ.вҖҷ.  This function вҲҳ has been optimized for numeric
arguments and computes the matrix product as known from linear algebra.

   For two-dimensional matrices A and B is function вҲҳ conceptually the
same as +.Г—:

   AвҲҳB вҶҗвҶ’ A +.Г— B

   However, there are some subtle differences between the function вҲҳ and
the operator +.Г—:

   вҖў A +.Г— B allows A and B to be of any rank, while AвҲҳB raises a RANK
     ERROR if the rank of A or B is more than 2.

   вҖў The product A +.Г— B can be a vector (e.g.  if A is a vector and B
     is a matrix), usually understood as row-vector.  In contrast (and
     more similar to linear algebra) AвҲҳB is always a matrix.
   вҖў In order to preserve the distinction between row vectors and column
     vectors the arguments A and B of вҲҳ are possibly reshaped according
     to the following rules:

        вҖў if A and/or B is a scalar then the normal (element-wise)
          product of A and B is computed.  That is, AвҲҳB вҶҗвҶ’ AГ—B.
        вҖў if A is a APL vector of length N then it is reshaped to a
          row-vector before AвҲҳB is computed.  In this context, the term
          row-vector shall refer to a matrix of shape (1 N).
        вҖў if B is a APL vector of length N then it is reshaped to a
          column-vector before AвҲҳB is computed.  In this context, the
          term column-vector shall refer to a matrix of shape (N 1).

     Examples:

                MвҶҗ2 2вҚҙ1 2 3 4   вҚқ a matrix
                VвҶҗ10 11         вҚқ a vector

                M +.Г— V
          32 74

                MвҲҳV
          32
          74

                V +.Г— M
          43 64

                VвҲҳM
          43 64

                вҚҙM +.Г— V   вҚқ the result is an (APL-) vector of length 2
          2
                вҚҙV +.Г— M   вҚқ the result is an (APL-) vector of length 2
          2
                вҚҙVвҲҳM       вҚқ the result is row vector
          1 2
                вҚҙMвҲҳV       вҚқ the result is column vector
          2 1

   вҖў A +.Г— B requires that the number of columns in A is equal to the
     number of rows in B. In contrast, AвҲҳB has no such requirement and
     will add 0-columns to A resp.  0-rows to B to match the shapes of A
     and B. Naturally, the multiplications of these 0-columns or 0-rows
     is not in fact performed, but optimized away.


File: apl.info,  Node: Monadic вү  (Nub Sieve),  Prev: Matrix Product,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.47 Monadic вү  (Nub Sieve)
==========================

The nub sieve ZвҶҗвү B of a value B is a Boolean vector Z with the same
shape as B and:

   Z[i] is 1 if B[i] is the first occurrence of B[i] in B and 0
otherwise.  For vectors B this can also be expressed as:

           вү  B вҶҗвҶ’ (BвҚіB)=(вҚівҚҙB)

   Examples:

           вү 'Hello, World.'
     1 1 1 0 1 1 1 1 0 1 0 1 1
           вү  1 (2 3) 4 (2 3) 5 6
     1 1 1 0 1 1


