5.4 Some APL2 Tests
===================

Before explaining the details of vector notation in GNU APL we would
like to share the results of some tests performed with IBM APL2 (again
the demo version for PCs).

* Menu:

* Test 1: Binding strength of []::
* Test 2: Binding strength of the left operand::


File: apl.info,  Node: Test 1: Binding strength of [],  Next: Test 2: Binding strength of the left operand,  Up: Some APL2 Tests

5.4.1 Test 1: Binding strength of []
------------------------------------

           вҚқ IBM APL2: Binding strength of []...

           вҚқ Test 1a.
           вҚқ
           1 2 3[2]
     RANK ERROR
           1 2 3[2]
               ^^

           вҚқ Test 1b.
           вҚқ
           'a' 'b' 'c'[2]
     RANK ERROR
           'ab' 'c'[2]
                ^  ^

           вҚқ Test 1c.
           вҚқ
           'abc'[b][2]
     b

   Test 1a: no surprise.  [] has the strongest binding and raises a RANK
ERROR when indexing the scalar 3.

   Test 1b: no surprise.  since it follows suit.

   Test 1c: no surprise for the binding strength.  This test confirms
the second quote on page 14 of the lrm.


File: apl.info,  Node: Test 2: Binding strength of the left operand,  Prev: Test 1: Binding strength of [],  Up: Some APL2 Tests

5.4.2 Test 2: Binding strength of the left operand
--------------------------------------------------

For this test we create a monadic defined function SHOW_NC, a monadic
defined operator OPER1, and a dyadic defined operator OPER2:

           вҚқ display the name class of BВҜB
           вҚқ
           вҲҮZвҶҗSHOW_NC BВҜB;N
            NвҶҗ8вҶ‘B,':'
            вҶ’(ВҜ1 0 1 2 3 4 = вҺ•NC BВҜB)/I U L V F O в—Ҡ ++
           I: вҶ’0, ZвҶҗ(8вҶ‘B), ': Invalid Name'
           U: вҶ’0, ZвҶҗ(8вҶ‘B), ': Unused Name'
           L: вҶ’0, ZвҶҗ(8вҶ‘B), ': Label'
           V: вҶ’0, ZвҶҗ(8вҶ‘B), ': Value', вҚҺBВҜB
           F: вҶ’0, ZвҶҗ(8вҶ‘B), ': Function'
           O: вҶ’0, ZвҶҗ(8вҶ‘B), ': Operator'
           вҲҮ

           вҚқ monadic operator
           вҚқ
           вҲҮZвҶҗA (LO OPER1) B
            SHOW_NC 'A'
            SHOW_NC 'LO'
            SHOW_NC 'OPER1'
            SHOW_NC 'B'
           вҲҮ

           вҚқ dyadic operator
           вҚқ
           вҲҮZвҶҗA (LO OPER2 RO) B
            SHOW_NC 'A'
            SHOW_NC 'LO'
            SHOW_NC 'OPER1'
            SHOW_NC 'RO'
            SHOW_NC 'B'
           вҲҮ

   The somewhat strange looking argument name BВҜB of SHOW_NC instead of
the rather frequent B was chosen to avoid name conflicts between the
right value argument of SHOW_NC and the right value argument the
operators under test (like OPER1 or OPER2).  Then:

           вҚқ Test 2a: binding of the left operand (literal LO)
           вҚқ
           11 22 33 OPER1 1 2 3
     A       : Unused Name
     LO      : Value  11 22 33
     OPER1   : Operator
     B       : Value  1 2 3

           вҚқ Test 2b: binding of the left operand (parser LO)
           вҚқ
           (UU VV WW)вҶҗ11 22 33
           UU VV WW OPER1 1 2 3
     A       : Unused Name
     LO      : Value  11 22 33
     OPER1   : Operator
     B       : Value  1 2 3

           вҚқ Test 2c. binding of the left operand (in parentheses)
           вҚқ
           11 22 (33 OPER1) 1 2 3
     A       : 11
     LO      : Value  22 33
     OPER1   : Operator
     B       : Value  1 2 3

           вҚқ Test 2d. binding of the right operand
           вҚқ
           11 22 33 'lop' OPER2 'rop' 1 2 3
     A       : Unused Name
     LO      : Value  11 22 33 lop
     OPER2   : Operator
     RO      : Value  rop
     B       : Value  1 2 3

   The results are rather interesting.  We will later on discuss a
potential difference between vector notation at tokenization time and
vector notation at execution time.  The same outcome of tests 2a.  and
2b.  demonstrates that IBM APL2 handles both variants in the same
fashion (supposedly because both cases are resolved at execution time).

   Test 2a.  proves that vector notation binds stronger than the left
operand to its dyadic operator.  Test 2c.  demonstrates how the binding
strengths can be undermined with parentheses.

   Test 2d.  proves that the right operand binds stronger than vector
notation.  However, this case is interesting from an iso.  Page 126 of
iso gives the following example for the dyadic rank operator:

           вҚқ example from ISO/IEC 13751 p.126
           вҚқ
           0 1 2вҢҪвҲҳ0 1 'ABC'
     ABC
     BCA
     CAB

   Comparing the results of Test 2d.  with GNU APL shows how iso
believes their example should be parsed:

           вҚқ Test 2e. (GNU APL):
           вҚқ
           0 1 2(вҢҪвҚӨ0 1) 'ABC'
     ABC
     BCA
     CAB

           вҚқ Test 2f. (GNU APL):
           вҚқ
           0 1 2(вҢҪвҚӨ0) 1 'ABC'
     LENGTH ERROR
           0 1 2(вҢҪвҚӨ0 0 0)1 'ABC'
           ^            ^

   NOTE: It is not possible to run tests 2e.  and 2f.  in IBM APL2
directly (because at least in the PC demo version of IBM APL2 the rank
operator вҚӨ is not implemented.  However using our defined function OPER2
above instead of вҚӨ shows that IBM APL2 evaluates the ISO example as 0 1
2(вҢҪвҲҳ0) 1 вҖҷABCвҖҷ (in accordance with lrm) and not as 0 1 2(вҢҪвҲҳ0 1) вҖҷABCвҖҷ as
iso suggests.

   Takeaways: the tests above teach us the following:

   вҖў Vector notation differs between:
        вҖў The ISO standard for APL,
        вҖў IBM APL2, and
        вҖў APL implementation of other vendors (including GNU APL).
   вҖў It is therefore impossible to accommodate both the ISO standard and
     IBM APL2 to 100% at the same time, but
   вҖў GNU APL tries to be as close as possible to one of them,
   вҖў The issues highlighted above can be easily avoided by always using
     parentheses around operators and their operands (even though they
     may appear to be redundant).  These parentheses are the (only) key
     to portable APL programs.


File: apl.info,  Node: Definitions,  Next: Unexpected Stranding,  Prev: Some APL2 Tests,  Up: Vector Notation

5.5 Definitions
===============

Definition: A (complete) strand consists of two (!)  or more adjacent
values in a defined function, or in a string being вҚҺвҖҷed, or on a line
entered in immediate execution mode.  Such values can be literals (like
in 1 2 3), but also values of variables or results of niladic functions.
A strand is always a vector and we call the values in a strand the items
of the strand.  Strand items can be simple (i.e.  numbers or single
characters) or nested (strings or other strands).  Strand items are
always (possibly nested) APL scalars.

   Definition: A literal strand is a strand whose items are only
literals (including nested literals like in 1 2 (3 4) 5).  Literal
strands are created when an APL expression is tokenized.  At that point
in time the literal strand is incomplete and more strand items may be
added to it when the statement is executed.

   Note: Strands are, in general, subject to what is known as unexpected
stranding, which occurs when an operator accept values as operands.
This is the case for the power operator вҚЈ and for the rank operator вҚӨ;
both can have values as right operands.  The clean way of avoiding
unexpected stranding is to put the operator and its operands into
parentheses, but the iso does not do that and in order to make the
examples in iso work, GNU APL has dedicated code for the rank and power
operators that prevents unexpected stranding for their right operand and
their right function value.  For defined operators this is not possible
because at tokenization time a defined operator is only a symbol whose
name class at execution time is unknown at tokenization time of its
caller.  For the same reason.  the binding strengths defined above can
not cure this kind of unexpected stranding.

   Definition: An extended literal strand is a strand whose items are
either literals (including nested literals) or particular simple
primitive function is with particular literal arguments.

   Definition: A mixed strand is a strand which is not a literal strand.

   Definition: A strand is open if more items can be appended to it.

   Definition: A strand is closed if it is not open.

   Definition: A strand is nested if at lease one of its items is
nested.

   Examples:

           1 2 3        вҚқ open literal strand

           1 2 (3вҚҙ4) 5     вҚқ open extended literal strand вҶҗвҶ’ 1 2 4 4 4 5
           1 2 (3/4) 5     вҚқ open extended literal strand вҶҗвҶ’ 1 2 4 4 4 5
          'ab' (вҚі3) 'ef'   вҚқ open extended literal strand вҶҗвҶ’ 'ab' (1 2 3) 'ef'

           VARвҶҗ1 2 3       вҚқ mixed strand item
           вҲҮZвҶҗFOO          вҚқ mixed strand item
            ZвҶҗ1 2 3
           вҲҮ

           1 VAR 3         вҚқ nested open mixed strand
           1 FOO 3         вҚқ nested open mixed strand

           (1 2 3)       вҚқ closed literal strand
           'abc'         вҚқ closed literal strand


