5.7 GNU APL Vector Notation
===========================

With the definitions from the previous section we can explain how GNU
APL has implemented vector notation:

   1.  GNU APL distinguishes between literal and mixed strands.  Literal
strands are combined into a single APL value at tokenization time.  This
is a very effective optimization (which can be disabled at ./configure
time).  In contrast, mixed strands are created at phrase matching time,
i.e.  when an APL expression is evaluated.  The tokenization of APL
expressions happens only once, while phrase matching occurs every time
when a statement is being executed and therefore moving major parts of
the strand building from phrase matching time to tokenization time can
bring substantial performance benefits.

   2.  The tokenization expands simple APL primitives with literal
arguments and short results into their literal equivalent.  Currently
the APL primitives NвҚҙB, N/B, NвҢҝB, ,B, вҚӘB, and вҠӮB are handled this way.

   3.  The tokenization of literal strands has dedicated code for
literal arguments of the power (вҚЈ) and rank operators (вҚӨ) to make make
it working like described in the ISO standard.  This is, in contrast to
defined operators, possible because the ISO standard defines in very
detail how its right operand needs to look like and how deviations shall
be handled (DOMAIN ERROR, LENGTH ERROR) etc.

   4.  The phrase matching of mixed strands builds the strand
step-by-step according to the following rules:

   вҖў two adjacent APL scalars A and B create a new open strand (with two
     strand items).  Each of the two scalars A or B can be simple (like
     numbers or single characters) or nested (like strings or closed
     strands).
   вҖў An APL scalar A adjacent to an open strand B prepends A to B. That
     is, BвҶҗA, B.
   вҖў An open strand A adjacent to an an APL scalar B appends B to A.
     That is, AвҶҗA, B.
   вҖў the previous two rules prevent two adjacent open strands, because
     the strand items of a potential open left strand A are prepended
     item by item to an open right strand B (which prevents the creation
     of a new open left strand while an open right strand exists,

   вҖў Like the normal APL evaluation, this procedure is preformed from
     the right to the left.
   вҖў if an open strand hits a closing parenthesis then a new phrase
     matching context is created in which the current procedure is
     abandoned until the corresponding opening parentheses has been
     processed.  The result of the expression in parentheses is then
     taken as the next strand item for the abandoned strand (if any).
   вҖў Any symbols encountered during this procedure are being resolved
     into scalars (possibly enclosing them if they are not).  Niladic
     functions are called to obtain their result.
   вҖў Likewise, any literal strands that were created at tokenization
     time are considered closed (which cause them to be enclosed when
     prepended or appended to an open mixed strand).
   вҖў If a strand is open then any other token (functions, operators,
     brackets, end-of-statement, etc.)  closes it.  The result is a
     single value for the strand.

   5.  The operators вҚЈ (power operator) and вҚӨ (rank operator), whose
right operand can be identified by the rules given in iso) have
dedicated code that "unstrands" the right operand from a strand that may
have been mistakenly created in 3.  above.

5.7.1 Example
-------------

Consider the following APL statement:

           вҲҮFOO
            "Time is now: " вҺ•TS
           вҲҮ

   When function FOO is created its single function line is being
tokenized.  The tokenization of the function line sees the string "Time
is now: " which is a literal token with 13 literal items (= single
characters).  The result of the tokenization is therefore 2 tokens: the
string and the system function вҺ•TS. Naturally вҺ•TS is the time stamp when
function FOO is called and not the time when function FOO is created.
Therefore the strand building stops at this point and leaves the string
as an (incomplete) strand because the strand building can not predict
when FOO will be called.  At this point the incomplete strand and the
system function вҺ•TS will become adjacent tokens in the function body of
FOO.

   Later on (or maybe never) FOO will be called.  The execution of FOO
(which goes from right to left) first sees the niladic token вҺ•TS, and
evaluates it to an integer vector B, say 2026 1 1 18 5 6 194.  Values
returned from functions, values of variables, and the literal strands
from the tokenization are all closed and incomplete, and so is B at this
point.  The execution then fetches the next token A, which is the
string.  The two adjacent tokens A and B now match the pattern A B in
the phrase table of the interpreter.  The corresponding phrase evaluator
for that pattern then prepends the items in A to B and replaces the two
tokens A and B with the new (single) token for the modified B. The next
token is then an END (for end of staement) token which causes B to be
printed.

   A final remark: It should be noted, that the phrase table defined in
iso is somewhat incomplete.  In particular the pattern A B above (which
performs the strand building in the execution phase) is not present in
iso.  Also, iso defines END tokens as used above, but no pattern in
which they appear.  All this has the unfortunate consequence that vector
notation is provided by every APL interpreter, but the details of it
differ considerably.  For example, 1 2 3[2] could be 2 in one
interpreter, but raise a RANK ERROR in another.  Even for different
interpreters of the same vendor.  The only reliable way to write
portable APL programs is to use (otherwise redundant) parentheses, in
particular around operators and their operands, and around strands that
are being indexed.


